{"title_page": "Little Angels International School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n | motto                   = Nothing is impossible.\n | location                = 9-7-14, Shimorenjaku, Mitaka-shi, Tokyo 181-0013, Japan\n | schooltype              = Private co-educational school\n | established             = 2002\n | head_of_school          = Edward Gilbreath\n | grades                  = PreK-12\n | accreditation           = Cambridge Assessment International Education\n | website                 = https://littleangels.jp/\n}}\n\n'''Little Angels International School''' (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30ca\u30b7\u30e7\u30ca\u30eb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb, also known as LAIS) is an K12 international school located in [[Mitaka, Tokyo|Mitaka]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. Founded in 2002, LAIS is committed to providing a multifaceted and an international education, to nurture students to be ambitious and life-long learners.\n\n==Composition==\nThe school includes Little Angels International School ('''LAIS'''; \u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30ca\u30b7\u30e7\u30ca\u30eb\u30fb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb) for full-time students and Little Angels English Academy (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30fb\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc) for after-school classes. The Little Angels International School has four divisions: Little Angels International Kindergarten (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u5e7c\u7a1a\u5712), the Little Angels International Elementary School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u5c0f\u5b66\u6821), Little Angels International Middle School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u4e2d\u5b66\u6821)\u3000and Little Angels High School\u3000(\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b66\u6821). The curriculum follows both Japanese government (\u6587\u90e8\u79d1\u5b66\u7701) guidelines and international English guidelines for education. The Little Angels Middle School and High School have received accreditation from the [[Cambridge International Examinations]].\n\nThe school also offers special classes for adults,<ref name=Joe>Joe, Melinda. \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2010/04/15/lifestyle/why-do-english-teachers-have-to-be-native-speakers/ Why do English teachers have to be native speakers?]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtLgLuBs?url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2010/04/15/lifestyle/why-do-english-teachers-have-to-be-native-speakers/ Archive]). ''[[The Japan Times]]''. April 15, 2010. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> under the name Little Angels Business School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30d3\u30b8\u30cd\u30b9\u30fb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb).<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/index_1.html Welcome to Little Angels Business School] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331212829/http://www.angelsenglish.com/index_1.html |date=2015-03-31 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe Mitaka Main Campus (\u4e09\u9df9\u672c\u6821) has all levels of education,<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/M1.html Mitaka Main Campus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051747/http://www.angelsenglish.com/M1.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"Address: 9-7-14, Shimorenjaku, Mitaka-shi, Tokyo 181-0013 \u3012181-0013 \u6771\u4eac\u4e09\u9df9\u5e02\u4e0b\u9023\u96c09-7-14\"</ref> including the school, kindergarten, English academy, and business school.<ref>[http://www.angelsenglish.com/AdSquarePage.html Home]. Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The [[Mitaka Station]] Campus (\u4e09\u9df9\u99c5\u6821) houses the Little Angels English Academy & International Kindergarten.<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/M2.html Mitaka Station Campus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051804/http://www.angelsenglish.com/M2.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"1-3-2, Kamirenjaku, Mitaka-shi, Tokyo 181-0012 \u3012181-0012 \u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u4e09\u9df9\u5e02\u4e0a\u9023\u96c0 1-3-2\"</ref>\n\nThe school's original kindergarten campus in Mitaka was previously a single family residence.<ref name=Saito>Saito, Mayumi. \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6Wud1KJX5?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070815123802/http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200709220042.html Weekend Beat: Japanese parents praise Tokyo's Indian schools]\" (). ''[[The Asahi Shimbun]]''/''[[International Herald Tribune]]''. September 22, 2007,  Tokyo edition. Retrieved on March 10, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Asahi-IHT-2007-Sep-22.pdf See alternate location] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WudAQOY8?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310005612/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Asahi-IHT-2007-Sep-22.pdf Archive]). \"A native of India, Sanku opened the kindergarten in Mitaka, western Tokyo, in 2004.\"</ref> The school previously had a campus in [[Kichij\u014dji]], [[Musashino, Tokyo|Musashino]].<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/Archived-files/2011/SpingSchool_App2011.pdf Spring School Program 2011 Application Form]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtP6LiP5?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309053150/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/Archived-files/2011/SpingSchool_App2011.pdf Archive]). Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"Little Angels International School 4-9-15, Honcho, Kichijoji, Musashino-shi, Tokyo 180-0004 (\u3012180-0004 \u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u6b66\u8535\u91ce\u5e02\u5409\u7965\u5bfa\u672c\u753a4-9-15)\"</ref>\n\n==History==\nJeevarani Angelina, a native of [[Chennai]], moved to Japan in 1990 and became a [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|non-resident Indian]]. Angelina, who is known as \"Rani Sanku\"{{#tag:ref|\"Sanku\" is the surname of Angelina's husband, Sarath Chandar Rao Sanku|group=note}} due to the ease in pronouncing it in Japanese,<ref name=\"Fackler\">Fackler, Martin. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02japan.html Losing an Edge, Japanese Envy India\u2019s Schools].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. January 2, 2008. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nytimes.pdf Alternate link] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtxtmB6Z?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309142533/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nytimes.pdf Archive]) \"Unlike other Indian schools, Ms. Angelina said, Little Angels was intended primarily for Japanese children, to meet the need she had found when she sent her sons to Japanese kindergarten.\"</ref> established an English-training school, Little Angels English Academy, in 2002.<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/history.html History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051805/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/history.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The kindergarten was started in 2004.<ref name=Saito/> In the beginning, the school had an enrollment of only 5 students; This, however, increased to 15 students in 2005 and 30 students in 2006. By February 2008, enrollment had reached 85 students.<ref name=Terada>Terada, Shinichi \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2008/12/28/national/more-parents-send-kids-to-indian-chinese-schools/#.VP_HpY7kfX8 More parents send kids to Indian, Chinese schools]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WsB2sjgJ?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090101015446/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20081228f1.html Archive]). ''[[The Japan Times]]''. Sunday December 28, 2008. Retrieved on March 11, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/JapanTimes2008.pdf Alternate link] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123005/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/JapanTimes2008.pdf |date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> Japanese student enrollment increased along with the general student enrollment.<ref name=TakizawaFukuda>Takizawa, Kosuke and Mai Fukuda. \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/News-2-12-2010.pdf Indian-style education gets an A] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6WtQFHjYA?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309053449/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/News-2-12-2010.pdf |date=2015-03-09 }}\" ([https://archive.is/20100218122609/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T100211006043.htm Archive]). ''[[The Daily Yomiuri]]''. February 12, 2010. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The school was scheduled to add the sixth grade in 2011. Melinda Joe of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' wrote that Little Angels \"even helped pave the way for other Indian international schools in Tokyo, such as the [[Global Indian International School (Tokyo)|Global Indian International School]] in [[Edogawa, Tokyo|Edogawa]].\"<ref name=Joe/>\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school has incorporated aspects of Montessori education,<ref name=Joe/> with additional group work and a decreased emphasis on memorization.<ref name=Fackler/> Students begin speaking English in public at ages 2<ref name=Oguma>Oguma, Naoto. \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Funlife-summer2012.pdf Little Angels Gakuen Encouraging Independence and Self-reliance]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtuI8GRy?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309132827/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Funlife-summer2012.pdf Archive]). ''[[Fun Life!]]''. No. 1, Summer 2012. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> or 3,<ref name=Terada/> and at age 4 they must only speak in English at school.<ref name=Oguma/> Mathematics instruction begins at age 2 and computer instruction begins at age 3; these ages are younger than the respective ages at traditional Japanese schools. Other classes include arts and crafts, dance,<ref name=Terada/> and science.<ref name=Asiansfresh>\"[https://www.webcitation.org/6WuZhSNPB?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310000147/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nikkei_E.pdf Asians offer fresh perspectives]\" (). ''[[The Nikkei Weekly]]''. August 27, 2007. Retrieved on March 10, 2015.</ref> The school uses Indian textbooks,<ref name=Terada/> but the school does not have Indian history classes.<ref name=Fackler/> Conversation, games, and songs are part of the curriculum.<ref name=Asiansfresh/>\n\n{{As of|2010}}, most students at this school and other Indian international schools who intend to study in the system until high school are aiming to enroll in universities outside Japan; the Tokyo Metropolitan Government considers this school and the other two Indian international schools in Tokyo to be \"unauthorized schools\" or schools which do not count as providing compulsory education under the School Education Law of Japan. A student who only attends \"unauthorized schools\" is ineligible to attend a university in Japan,<ref name=TakizawaFukuda/> unless they complete an accepted international curriculum such as the International Baccalaureate,<ref>Iwasaki, Kumiko. \"[http://www.nippon.com/en/currents/d00096/ Will the International Baccalaureate Take Off in Japan?]\" Nippon.com, [[Nippon Communications Foundation]]. December 4, 2013. Retrieved on August 13, 2015.</ref><ref>Abrioux, Marc and Jill Rutherford. ''Introducing the IB Diploma Programme'' (Cambridge resources for the IB diploma). [[Cambridge University Press]], February 14, 2013. {{ISBN|1107606284}}, 9781107606289. p. [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=D1UGVo8AI2AC&pg=PT47#v=onepage&q&f=false 1].</ref> or [[Cambridge International Examinations]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Little Angels - About Us|url=http://angelsenglish.com/our-history/|website=LAIS Homepage}}</ref>\n\nThe school is currently undergoing evaluation by the Council of International Schools to provide opportunities for the graduates to enter Japanese and foreign universities.\n\n==Student body==\nIn 2008, it had 45 students, one of whom was Indian.<ref name=Fackler/> Japanese people made up 80% of the students {{as of|2010|lc=y}}. Children of mixed marriages and children from other countries make up the remainder.<ref name=Joe/> {{As of|2012}}, the percentage of Japanese students rose to almost 90%.<ref name=Oguma/>  {{As of|2015}}, the number of students rose to almost 90 students spanning from pre-school to middle school.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Teaching staff==\nIn 2008, there were four full-time teachers, three of whom were non-Japanese.<ref name=Fackler/> {{As of|2008}}, the majority of the teachers started [[English language|English]] early in their lives.<ref name=Terada/> These instructors originated from [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]]; including India, Indonesia, and Nepal.<ref name=Joe/> As of 2015, the school has teachers from Australia, England, Greece, India, Jamaica, Nepal, Philippines, the United States and have a diverse faculty.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Tokyo|India|Schools}}\n* [[Indians in Japan]]\n\nJapanese schools in India:\n* [[Japanese School of Mumbai]]\n* [[Japanese School New Delhi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Further reading==\nVideo files:\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/LA-CNN.mp4 LA-CNN.mp4]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuilYssW?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310021406/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/LA-CNN.mp4 Archive]). ''[[CNN]]''. January 17, 2008.\n\nAudio files:\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/ABC-Radio.mp3 ABC-Radio.mp3]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuiZXP1G?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310021445/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/ABC-Radio.mp3 Archive]). ''[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Radio]]''. - Interview of Angelina\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/NikkeiNewsWeekly.mp3 NikkeiNewsWeekly.mp3]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuiUwdQ3?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310021545/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/NikkeiNewsWeekly.mp3 Archive]). ''[[Nikkei News Weekly]]'' podcast. Circa 2007. - Interview regarding \"Asians Offer Fresh Perspectives\" from ''[[The Nikkei Weekly]]''.\n{{in lang|ja}}\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Yomiuri29-12-2010.pdf \u7559\u5b66\u7d4c\u9a13\u306e\u89aa\u300c\u82f1\u8a9e\u8eab\u306b\u3064\u3051\u3066\u300d]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Wtr2rpTg?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309124108/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Yomiuri29-12-2010.pdf Archive]). ''[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]''. December 12, 2010 ([[Heisei]] 22).\n* [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/GlitterMag2010.pdf Article in] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuWgfaEw?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309231711/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/GlitterMag2010.pdf Archive]). ''[[Glitter (magazine)|Glitter]]'' (\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30bf\u30fc)/''Mama & Kids'' (\u30de\u30de\uff06\u30ad\u30c3\u30ba). Volume 1, No. 100. November 2010.\n* [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/President_Baby_Nov-13-2010.pdf Article in] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuXQIUXZ?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309232739/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/President_Baby_Nov-13-2010.pdf Archive]). ''[[President Baby]]'' (\u30d7\u30ec\u30b8\u30c7\u30f3\u30c8\u30d9\u30fc\u30d3\u30fc). November 13, 2010.\n* [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/sukusuku.pdf Article in] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuakFf3T?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310001845/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/sukusuku.pdf Archive]) ''{{ill|SukuSuku Paradise|ja|\u3059\u304f\u3059\u304f\u30d1\u30e9\u30c0\u30a4\u30b9}}'' (\u3059\u304f\u3059\u304f\u30d1\u30e9\u30c0\u30a4\u30b9), January 2008.\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/kodomonojikan2007.pdf Why India now?]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Wub5XvCW?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310002205/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/kodomonojikan2007.pdf Archive]). ''[[Kodomojikan]]'' (\u3053\u3069\u3082\u3058\u304b\u3093). November 2007. - [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Kodomonijikan-english.pdf  English translation] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Wub15QQo?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310002147/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Kodomonijikan-english.pdf Archive]).\n\n==External links==\n*[https://littleangels.jp/ Little Angels International School]\n{{Mitaka, Tokyo}}\n{{International schools in Tokyo}}\n{{Indian international schools}}\n{{coord missing|Tokyo}}\n\n[[Category:International schools in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in Japan]]\n[[Category:Mitaka, Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Musashino, Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Indian international schools in Japan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2002]]\n", "text_old": "'''Little Angels International School''' (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30ca\u30b7\u30e7\u30ca\u30eb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb, also known as LAIS) is an K12 international school located in [[Mitaka, Tokyo|Mitaka]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. Founded in 2002, LAIS is committed to providing a multifaceted and an international education, to nurture students to be ambitious and life-long learners.\n\n==Composition==\nThe school includes Little Angels International School ('''LAIS'''; \u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30ca\u30b7\u30e7\u30ca\u30eb\u30fb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb) for full-time students and Little Angels English Academy (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30b7\u30e5\u30fb\u30a2\u30ab\u30c7\u30df\u30fc) for after-school classes. The Little Angels International School has four divisions: Little Angels International Kindergarten (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u5e7c\u7a1a\u5712), the Little Angels International Elementary School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u5c0f\u5b66\u6821), Little Angels International Middle School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u4e2d\u5b66\u6821)\u3000and Little Angels High School\u3000(\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u9ad8\u7b49\u5b66\u6821). The curriculum follows both Japanese government (\u6587\u90e8\u79d1\u5b66\u7701) guidelines and international English guidelines for education. The Little Angels Middle School and High School have received accreditation from the [[Cambridge International Examinations]].\n\nThe school also offers special classes for adults,<ref name=Joe>Joe, Melinda. \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2010/04/15/lifestyle/why-do-english-teachers-have-to-be-native-speakers/ Why do English teachers have to be native speakers?]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtLgLuBs?url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2010/04/15/lifestyle/why-do-english-teachers-have-to-be-native-speakers/ Archive]). ''[[The Japan Times]]''. April 15, 2010. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> under the name Little Angels Business School (\u30ea\u30c8\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30a7\u30eb\u30b9\u30fb\u30d3\u30b8\u30cd\u30b9\u30fb\u30b9\u30af\u30fc\u30eb).<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/index_1.html Welcome to Little Angels Business School] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331212829/http://www.angelsenglish.com/index_1.html |date=2015-03-31 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe Mitaka Main Campus (\u4e09\u9df9\u672c\u6821) has all levels of education,<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/M1.html Mitaka Main Campus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051747/http://www.angelsenglish.com/M1.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"Address: 9-7-14, Shimorenjaku, Mitaka-shi, Tokyo 181-0013 \u3012181-0013 \u6771\u4eac\u4e09\u9df9\u5e02\u4e0b\u9023\u96c09-7-14\"</ref> including the school, kindergarten, English academy, and business school.<ref>[http://www.angelsenglish.com/AdSquarePage.html Home]. Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The [[Mitaka Station]] Campus (\u4e09\u9df9\u99c5\u6821) houses the Little Angels English Academy & International Kindergarten.<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/M2.html Mitaka Station Campus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051804/http://www.angelsenglish.com/M2.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"1-3-2, Kamirenjaku, Mitaka-shi, Tokyo 181-0012 \u3012181-0012 \u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u4e09\u9df9\u5e02\u4e0a\u9023\u96c0 1-3-2\"</ref>\n\nThe school's original kindergarten campus in Mitaka was previously a single family residence.<ref name=Saito>Saito, Mayumi. \"[https://www.webcitation.org/6Wud1KJX5?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20070815123802/http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200709220042.html Weekend Beat: Japanese parents praise Tokyo's Indian schools]\" (). ''[[The Asahi Shimbun]]''/''[[International Herald Tribune]]''. September 22, 2007,  Tokyo edition. Retrieved on March 10, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Asahi-IHT-2007-Sep-22.pdf See alternate location] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WudAQOY8?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310005612/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Asahi-IHT-2007-Sep-22.pdf Archive]). \"A native of India, Sanku opened the kindergarten in Mitaka, western Tokyo, in 2004.\"</ref> The school previously had a campus in [[Kichij\u014dji]], [[Musashino, Tokyo|Musashino]].<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/Archived-files/2011/SpingSchool_App2011.pdf Spring School Program 2011 Application Form]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtP6LiP5?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309053150/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/Archived-files/2011/SpingSchool_App2011.pdf Archive]). Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. \"Little Angels International School 4-9-15, Honcho, Kichijoji, Musashino-shi, Tokyo 180-0004 (\u3012180-0004 \u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u6b66\u8535\u91ce\u5e02\u5409\u7965\u5bfa\u672c\u753a4-9-15)\"</ref>\n\n==History==\nJeevarani Angelina, a native of [[Chennai]], moved to Japan in 1990 and became a [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|non-resident Indian]]. Angelina, who is known as \"Rani Sanku\"{{#tag:ref|\"Sanku\" is the surname of Angelina's husband, Sarath Chandar Rao Sanku|group=note}} due to the ease in pronouncing it in Japanese,<ref name=\"Fackler\">Fackler, Martin. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02japan.html Losing an Edge, Japanese Envy India\u2019s Schools].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. January 2, 2008. Retrieved on March 9, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nytimes.pdf Alternate link] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtxtmB6Z?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309142533/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nytimes.pdf Archive]) \"Unlike other Indian schools, Ms. Angelina said, Little Angels was intended primarily for Japanese children, to meet the need she had found when she sent her sons to Japanese kindergarten.\"</ref> established an English-training school, Little Angels English Academy, in 2002.<ref>\"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/history.html History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309051805/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/history.html |date=2015-03-09 }}.\" Little Angels International School. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The kindergarten was started in 2004.<ref name=Saito/> In the beginning, the school had an enrollment of only 5 students; This, however, increased to 15 students in 2005 and 30 students in 2006. By February 2008, enrollment had reached 85 students.<ref name=Terada>Terada, Shinichi \"[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2008/12/28/national/more-parents-send-kids-to-indian-chinese-schools/#.VP_HpY7kfX8 More parents send kids to Indian, Chinese schools]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WsB2sjgJ?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090101015446/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20081228f1.html Archive]). ''[[The Japan Times]]''. Sunday December 28, 2008. Retrieved on March 11, 2015. [http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/JapanTimes2008.pdf Alternate link] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123005/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/JapanTimes2008.pdf |date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> Japanese student enrollment increased along with the general student enrollment.<ref name=TakizawaFukuda>Takizawa, Kosuke and Mai Fukuda. \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/News-2-12-2010.pdf Indian-style education gets an A] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6WtQFHjYA?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309053449/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/News-2-12-2010.pdf |date=2015-03-09 }}\" ([https://archive.is/20100218122609/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T100211006043.htm Archive]). ''[[The Daily Yomiuri]]''. February 12, 2010. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> The school was scheduled to add the sixth grade in 2011. Melinda Joe of ''[[The Japan Times]]'' wrote that Little Angels \"even helped pave the way for other Indian international schools in Tokyo, such as the [[Global Indian International School (Tokyo)|Global Indian International School]] in [[Edogawa, Tokyo|Edogawa]].\"<ref name=Joe/>\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school has incorporated aspects of Montessori education,<ref name=Joe/> with additional group work and a decreased emphasis on memorization.<ref name=Fackler/> Students begin speaking English in public at ages 2<ref name=Oguma>Oguma, Naoto. \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Funlife-summer2012.pdf Little Angels Gakuen Encouraging Independence and Self-reliance]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WtuI8GRy?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150309132827/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Funlife-summer2012.pdf Archive]). ''[[Fun Life!]]''. No. 1, Summer 2012. Retrieved on March 9, 2015.</ref> or 3,<ref name=Terada/> and at age 4 they must only speak in English at school.<ref name=Oguma/> Mathematics instruction begins at age 2 and computer instruction begins at age 3; these ages are younger than the respective ages at traditional Japanese schools. Other classes include arts and crafts, dance,<ref name=Terada/> and science.<ref name=Asiansfresh>\"[https://www.webcitation.org/6WuZhSNPB?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150310000147/http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/Nikkei_E.pdf Asians offer fresh perspectives]\" (). ''[[The Nikkei Weekly]]''. August 27, 2007. Retrieved on March 10, 2015.</ref> The school uses Indian textbooks,<ref name=Terada/> but the school does not have Indian history classes.<ref name=Fackler/> Conversation, games, and songs are part of the curriculum.<ref name=Asiansfresh/>\n\n{{As of|2010}}, most students at this school and other Indian international schools who intend to study in the system until high school are aiming to enroll in universities outside Japan; the Tokyo Metropolitan Government considers this school and the other two Indian international schools in Tokyo to be \"unauthorized schools\" or schools which do not count as providing compulsory education under the School Education Law of Japan. A student who only attends \"unauthorized schools\" is ineligible to attend a university in Japan,<ref name=TakizawaFukuda/> unless they complete an accepted international curriculum such as the International Baccalaureate,<ref>Iwasaki, Kumiko. \"[http://www.nippon.com/en/currents/d00096/ Will the International Baccalaureate Take Off in Japan?]\" Nippon.com, [[Nippon Communications Foundation]]. December 4, 2013. Retrieved on August 13, 2015.</ref><ref>Abrioux, Marc and Jill Rutherford. ''Introducing the IB Diploma Programme'' (Cambridge resources for the IB diploma). [[Cambridge University Press]], February 14, 2013. {{ISBN|1107606284}}, 9781107606289. p. [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=D1UGVo8AI2AC&pg=PT47#v=onepage&q&f=false 1].</ref> or [[Cambridge International Examinations]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Little Angels - About Us|url=http://angelsenglish.com/our-history/|website=LAIS Homepage}}</ref>\n\nThe school is currently undergoing evaluation by the Council of International Schools to provide opportunities for the graduates to enter Japanese and foreign universities.\n\n==Student body==\nIn 2008, it had 45 students, one of whom was Indian.<ref name=Fackler/> Japanese people made up 80% of the students {{as of|2010|lc=y}}. Children of mixed marriages and children from other countries make up the remainder.<ref name=Joe/> {{As of|2012}}, the percentage of Japanese students rose to almost 90%.<ref name=Oguma/>  {{As of|2015}}, the number of students rose to almost 90 students spanning from pre-school to middle school.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==Teaching staff==\nIn 2008, there were four full-time teachers, three of whom were non-Japanese.<ref name=Fackler/> {{As of|2008}}, the majority of the teachers started [[English language|English]] early in their lives.<ref name=Terada/> These instructors originated from [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]]; including India, Indonesia, and Nepal.<ref name=Joe/> As of 2015, the school has teachers from Australia, England, Greece, India, Jamaica, Nepal, Philippines, the United States and have a diverse faculty.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Tokyo|India|Schools}}\n* [[Indians in Japan]]\n\nJapanese schools in India:\n* [[Japanese School of Mumbai]]\n* [[Japanese School New Delhi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Further reading==\nVideo files:\n* \"[http://www.angelsenglish.com/about/MediaC/LA-CNN.mp4 LA-CNN.mp4]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6WuilYssW?url=