sired location, lifting medium i.e. pumps are required. Depending upon the Duty point head, discharge the different types of pumps are selected.\n:''Conveying Medium''-Rising main may be of [[steel]], [[concrete]] or any other suitable material.\n\n==Lift Irrigation Scheme in Telangana==\nIn India, the [[National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development]] reports that there are 1401 lift irrigation schemes financed by them.  These schemes irrigate 22000 hectares of land, and have a total financial outlay of Rs. 6462.5 million. However, as many as 573 of these schemes are defunct, mainly due to poor distribution of water. Other schemes have been financed by the [[Government of India|government]], sugar factories, or individual farmers. \n\nWater shortage is a huge predicament for a country like India which still relies on [[monsoon]] rains for much of its agricultural practices. As weather patterns become increasingly uncertain with time, most likely due to [[global warming]], being prepared to cope with water shortages in the future is essential. Rural communities as well as huge population which are greatly affected by [[water scarcity]] are the people living in drought-prone areas or in semi-arid up-lands. Much of these disadvantaged areas are also inhibited by tribal villages in many parts of India and are also backward in agricultural practices. These tribal villages are mainly self-sustained in their living habits and rely heavily on the paddy crops for endurance. It is becoming progressively more intricate to maintain tribal lifestyle due to uncertain weather patterns resulting in dwindling of agricultural production over time and all the more increasing the burden on state to raise their standard of living in terms of [[food security]], education, and health care. It is also seen, when time gets tough, villagers generally tend to migrate on a seasonal basis to seek other means of livelihood. Such seasonal migration of entire village population also affects their settled life hampering their children\u2019s education as well as their access to other developmental support coming from state.\n\nIt is consequently important to help their agriculture instead in order to reduce the incidence of [[Human migration|migration]] in such areas. This can only be achieved by ensuring there is sufficient crop to feed villagers and to sell at market to allow income generation. Irrigation is the essential input to the soil for any vegetation to grow. It is used to lend a hand in the growing of agricultural crops, maintenance of landscapes, and potentials of vegetation by restoring humidity / [[humus]] in depleted soils of dry areas and during periods of insufficient rainfall. Additionally, irrigation also has a few other uses in crop production, which include shielding plants against frost, suppressing weed and wild vegetation in grain fields and helping in preventing [[soil erosion]]. In contrast, agriculture that relies only on direct rainfall is referred to as rain-fed agriculture, or if it falls in semi-arid regions, it is called dry land farming. Irrigation is often studied together with drainage, which is the natural or artificial removal of surface and subsurface water from a given area. Various types of [[irrigation]] techniques differ in how the water obtained from the source, and is distributed within the field. In general, the aim is to supply water homogeneously to the entire field, so that each land patch has enough amount of water it needs, neither too much nor too little. Irrigation Schemes primarily comprises canal irrigation and lift irrigation schemes. In such schemes, the most important and yet the most neglected part is the local ownership and institutions of farmers taking operative and m responsibilities.\n\n==Participatory Irrigation Management==\nThe main purpose of the irrigation reform programme in [[Andhra Pradesh]] is to improve the sustainability and productivity of irrigation through sharing irrigation management responsibility with the farmers organized as Water Users Associations. Towards this the State government enacted the Andhra Pradesh Farmers Management of Irrigation System Act in 1997. Presently, water users\u2019 organizations under the APFMIS Act is constituted at three different levels in major irrigation projects - [[Water user associations|Water Users Associations]] (WUAs) at the minor canal level, Distributor Committees (DCs) at the distributor canal level and Project Committee (PCs) at the main canal level. In medium irrigation project they are constituted at two levels \u2013 WUA at the minor canal level and PC at the main canal level. In minor irrigation tanks only a WUA is constituted covering the whole tank command. A total of 10,748 WUAs have been constituted \u2013 2261 in major irrigation projects, 410 in medium irrigation projects and 8077 in minor irrigation tanks.\n\nThe water users\u2019 organizations undertake the responsibilities of seasonal crop planning and irrigation water regulation, O&M works on canal system and assist in tax collection. To facilitate the functioning of the water users\u2019 organizations the State government re-ploughs 100% of the irrigation water tax collected from them. The water tax collection and [[plough back]] for O&M to water users\u2019 organizations over the last 5 years is given in the Table below:<ref>[http://www.naandi.org/anual_report/2004-2005.pdf Naandi Annual Report 2004-2005]</ref><ref>[http://www.naandi.org/anual_report/1_Naandi_AR%2805-06%29.pdf Naandi Annual Report 2005-2006]</ref><ref name=\"li_case\">[http://liftirrigation.org/html/case_study.html Case study] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050207025644/http://liftirrigation.org/html/case_study.html |date=2005-02-07 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Collection (in Rs. million)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | O&M Plan (in Rs. millions)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Plough Back (in Rs. millions)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | Budgetary Support (in Rs. millions)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | 2005-06\n|560\n|NA\n|0\n|0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | 2006-07\n|670\n|NA\n|300\n|0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | 2007-08\n|750\n|NA\n|300\n|0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | 2008-09\n|1150\n|2000\n|600\n|1400\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#efefef;\" | 2009-10\n|1320 (Projected)\n|1600\n|1000\n|600\n|}\n\n==Maintenance of Lift Irrigation Schemes in AP==\nIn Andhra Pradesh, Andhra Pradesh State Irrigation Development Corporation (APSIDC) was established in 1974 to exploit the ground and surface water potential through lifts in a big way. Till now APSIDC has constructed around 1150 Lift Irrigation Schemes, creating an irrigation potential of 430000 acres. There are several LIS constructed by Irrigation & Power Department, private farmers and farmer societies, creating an irrigation potential of about 2,70,000 acres. The schemes constructed by I & P D are being maintained by the department even now. APSIDC has constructed some schemes with the share capital (25%) given by the government and the balance 75% capital raised through Nationalized banks refinanced by NABARD. These schemes were maintained by APSIDC (IDC) till 1995. Later all these schemes were either handed over to the farmer's societies for maintenance or kept under lock and key. Some other schemes were constructed by IDC on agency basis as deposit works. These were handed over either to the beneficiary societies or sponsoring agencies for maintenance after commissioning.<ref name=\"li_case\"/>\n\n==Maintenance of the LI Scheme by the Beneficiary Committee Society==\nThere are several parameters influencing the maintainability of LIS by the beneficiaries. The inter and intra village rivalries, the empowerment and social involvement levels of the farmers, the electricity tariff rates (now it has been made free), quality and quantity of power supply, the quality and performance of different components of the LIS and the performance of whole LIS as a system etc.\nThe Tyullar LIS was handed over to the beneficiaries during 2008. The scheme is being maintained by the beneficiaries successfully from 2008.\n\nThe profit and loss statement of the Tyullar LI Society shows that income over expenditure in the last 3 years is Rs 22, 12,551/- The society is cash rich and ready to meet any un-expected expenditure due to any contingency in the scheme. This ensures sustainability of maintenance by the society.\n\n==Farmer\u2019s Associations manage LI Schemes and pay for O&M==\nOne of the main issues confronting irrigation system transfer is to decide on who would pay the cost of operation and maintenance of the system. APSIDC has handed over the LI schemes to Farmer\u2019s Associations to operate, maintain and manage.\nThe Farmers\u2019 Association members, who take over a scheme, will sign an agreement among themselves to share water as well as the cost of operation and maintenance equitably. The basis of each family\u2019s contribution will be worked out by the members and included in the annex to the MOA between the FA and APSIDC. The SO will facilitate this process and may sign as a witness.\n\n==Social Engineering Activities==\nCapacity Building and community organization are the most important factors in strengthening the Lift Irrigation Societies. There are many defunct LI Schemes existing in [[Andhra Pradesh]], the main reason is the stakeholders did not have the capacity to run by themselves as per the guidelines envisaged. Therefore, the AP State Irrigation Development Corporation has decided to entrust the aspect of Social Engineering component to the identified [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]]\u2019s (Support Organization) with a view to make the scheme sustainable.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Irrigation]]\n[[Category:Irrigation in India]]\n[[Category:Lift irrigation schemes| ]]\n", "name_user": "Hardipsinhjadeja1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lift_irrigation"}
{"title_page": "Kabali (film)", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Kabali|the village in Turkey|Kabal\u0131, Vezirk\u00f6pr\u00fc}}\n{{short description|2016 film directed by Pa. Ranjith}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kabali\n| image          = Kabali poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Pa. Ranjith]]\n| producer       = [[Kalaipuli S. Thanu]]\n| writer         = Pa. Ranjith\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Rajinikanth]]\n* [[Radhika Apte]]\n* [[Sai Dhanshika]]\n* [[Winston Chao]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Santhosh Narayanan]]\n| cinematography = [[Murali G]]\n| editing        = [[Praveen K. L.|Praveen K.L]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Editor Praveen KL's hint about the Teaser release of 'Kabali'??|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/editor-praveen-kl-starts-working-on-superstar-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-kabali-tamil-news-153814.html|website=Indiaglitz|publisher=Indiaglitz|accessdate=15 July 2016|date=March 2016}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[S. Thanu|V Creations]]\n| distributor    = {{ubl|[[Gemini Film Circuit]]|[[Maxlab Cinemas and Entertainments]]|[[Fox Star Studios]]|Malik Stream Corporations}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2016|07|21|[[Malaysia]]|ref1=<ref name = BWAnj>{{cite web|url=http://www.catchnews.com/regional-cinema/rajinikanth-starrer-kabali-s-first-premiere-to-be-held-in-malaysia-here-are-the-complete-details-rajinikanth-kabali-movie-latest-news-1467726038.html|title = Rajinikanth starrer Kabali's first premiere to be held in Malaysia. |publisher=Catch News|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>|2016|07|22|Worldwide}}\n| runtime        = 152 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/superstar-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-dhanshika-kabali-censor-u-certificate-run-time-tamil-news-162995.html|title=Kabali:censor and running time detail|date=11 July 2016|access-date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{Estimation}} {{INR|100 [[crore]]}}<ref name=\"Kabali\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-1st-day-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-film-strikes-gold-its-opening-day-687566|title='Kabali' 1st day collection at box office: Rajinikanth's film beats first day records of 'Vedalam' to become biggest opener in TN|date=23 July 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = Disputed (see [[#Disputed gross figures|box office]])\n}}\n\n'''''Kabali''''' is a 2016 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[Action film|action]] [[crime film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kabali.htm|title=Kabali (2016)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/kabali-2016|title=KABALI|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]}}</ref> written and directed by [[Pa. Ranjith]] and produced by [[S. Thanu|Kalaipuli S. Thanu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kabali-the-album-of-rajinikanths-film-will-be-launched-on-june-11/1/683230.html|title=Kabali: Music album of Rajinikanths gangster film to be launched on June 11|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> The film plot concerns the gang war between Kabaleeswaran (played by [[Rajinikanth]]) and Tony Lee (portrayed by [[Winston Chao]]). [[Radhika Apte]], [[Sai Dhanshika]], [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]], [[Dinesh Ravi|Dinesh]], [[Kalaiyarasan]], and [[John Vijay]] also appear in pivotal roles.\n\nPrincipal photography for the film began on 21 August 2015 in [[Chennai]]. While filming mostly occurred in [[Malaysia]], some scenes were shot in [[Bangkok]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioadhurs.nz/album/kabali/|title=Kabali (2016)|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in Tamil along with dubbed versions in Telugu and Hindi on 22 July 2016, while the film was released in Malay a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/kabali-malay-version-to-release-on-july-29-news-tamil-qhekPIdgacdcd.html|title='Kabali' Malay version to release on July 29|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"HTDelayFilmDate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/makers-launch-kabali-app-even-as-its-release-is-delayed-by-two-weeks/story-XuGJEknDjIuvmLZHQtr6CI.html|title=Makers launch Kabali app even as its release is delayed by two weeks|date=11 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-releases-sends-fans-into-frenzy-from-4-a-m/articleshow/53331557.cms|title=Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' releases, sends fans into frenzy from 4 a.m&nbsp;\u2014 The Economic Times|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> ''Kabali'' was released on 3200 screens in [[India]], of which 2200 were in [[South India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2176|title=Kabali (Hindi) And Madaari First Day Business 2200 1000 3200}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!--This plot summary refers to the general version of the film and not the Malaysian one-->\nA [[Kuala Lumpur]]\u2013based [[Crime boss|don]] Kabaleeswaran alias Kabali is released after spending 25 years in prison on a false charge of starting a massacre at a local [[Hindu]] temple that killed many, including his wife Kumudhavalli. He immediately resumes charge of his old gang and soon confronts Loganathan, a [[drug smuggling|drug smuggler]]. Loga insults Kumudha, saying that she would have been sold into prostitution had she been alive. In retaliation, Kabali rams his car into Loga, killing him; however, the incident makes him believe that his wife may be still alive. Later, Kabali survives an assassination attempt by Tamizh Kumaran alias Kumaran, whose father Tamilmaaran was killed by Kabali when Kumaran was a young boy. The next day, at a function organised by the Free Life Foundation School, a school started by Kabali's friend Ameer to reform youngsters involved in criminal activities, Kabali talks about his past.\n\nKabali was the protege of Tamilmaaran's father Tamilnesan, a don who fought for the rights of [[Tamil Malaysians]]. Tamilnesan was killed by Veerasekaran, a member of his gang who disliked his rules such as not involving in illegal activities like drug smuggling and prostitution. Following Tamilnesan's death, Kabali took charge of Tamilnesan's gang. Veera manipulated Tamilmaaran by telling him that he, being Tamilnesan's son, should lead the gang and not Kabali. Tamilmaaran invited Kabali and a pregnant Kumudha for a temple function. However, this was revealed to be a trap as Veera and his men confronted Kabali and Kumudha at the function. In the ensuing scuffle, Kabali was brutally attacked while Kumudha was shot and seemingly killed. Kabali then killed Tamilmaaran for his betrayal in front of a young Kumaran and was soon arrested on a false charge of instigating the massacre.\n\nKumaran, after hearing Kabali's speech, realises his mistake and apologises to him. He tells him that Velu, one of Veera's henchmen who was present at the temple massacre, is aware of what happened to Kumudha. Kabali then leaves for [[Thailand]], where Velu is residing. On confronting Velu, he learns that his daughter is still alive. At this juncture, Kabali is confronted by Yogi, a [[contract killing|contract killer]] hired by Veera and his boss Tony Lee, who heads the rival Gang 43 in Kuala Lumpur, to eliminate Kabali. Yogi instead kills the men who had come with her and reveals herself to Kabali as his daughter, who had been raised by Velu. She also tells him that Kumudha is still alive and is living with a French family in [[Pondicherry|Puducherry]]. Kabali and Yogi then leave for Puducherry, where, after several days of searching, they reunite with Kumudha and spend a few days with her there. While in Puducherry, Kabali and his family are attacked by men sent by Tony. However, Kabali and Yogi fight them off and escape safely with Kumudha.\n\nKabali and his family soon return to Kuala Lumpur, where he is told that Ameer has been severely injured in a car accident set up by Tony; his henchman Jeeva was brutally chopped to pieces by Tony after refusing to join Gang 43; and Gang 43 had destroyed the Free Life Foundation School and started to control the Kuala Lumpur underworld, eliminating any gang who dared to oppose them. On hearing all this, Kabali decides to finish Veera and Tony. He and his family attend the 100th birthday party for a respected Malaysian don Ang Lee, who had invited all gangs, including Gang 43. At the party, Kabali starts a shootout with the help of Kumaran, which ends with him killing Veera and Tony.\n\nSome months later, Kabali, Kumudha, Kumaran, and Yogi attend a function organised by the Free Life Foundation. One of the Free Life alumni, a youngster named Tiger, who is known to be aggressive and reckless, walks up to Kabali, with scenes showing him speaking to the police prior to the function. The screen cuts to black, and the sound of a gun clicking and a gunshot afterwards is heard.<!--do ''not'' write that the film ends ambiguously as it may show POV-->\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Kabaliswaran (Kabali), the head of Malaysian Gangster group '00'.\n* [[Radhika Apte]] as Kumudhavalli Kabaliswaran, Kabali's wife\n* [[Sai Dhanshika]] as Yogitha Kabaleeswaran, Kabali's daughter who is a contract killer in Thailand.\n* [[Winston Chao]] as Tony Lee, industrialist, businessman and a head of Malaysian Gangster group '43'.\n* [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]] as Veerasekaran, the second head of '43'\n* [[Attakathi Dinesh|Dinesh]] as Jeeva, Kabali's gang member.\n* [[Kalaiyarasan]] as Thamizh Kumaran (Kumaran), Tamizh Nesan's grandson and Tamizh Maran's son. He is a teacher in Kabali's school.\n* [[John Vijay]] as Ameer, Kabali's sidekick/trusted aide.\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Tamizh Nesan, the founder of '00' to protect Malaysian Tamizhans (Guest Appearance)\n* [[Riythvika]] as Meena, a drug-addicted girl who joins Kabali's school for a reason to safe from drugs. Later, Kabali adopts her as his daughter.\n* [[Sangili Murugan]] as Palace Owner\n* [[Rosyam Nor]] as Tony's sidekick\n* [[Charles Vinoth]] as Tamizh Maaran, Tamizha Nesan's son and Kabali's best friend.\n* [[Mime Gopi]] as Loganathan, '43' second main member to do drug supply.\n* [[R. Amarendran]] as Velu/Venu, Veera's henchman.\n* Lishesh as Seeni, '43' main member to do money laundry.\n* [[Kabali Vishwanth|Visvanth]] as Jai\n* Hari Krishnan as Tiger, school student who encounters Kabali in the end.\n* Gajaraj as Marthandam, Kabali's teammate in young age but later works for Gang '43'.\n* Sampath Ram as Sampath, Kabali's teammate.\n* [[Rama (actress)|Rama]] as Mallika\n* [[Uday Mahesh]] as Durai\n* [[Poster Nandakumar|Nandakumar]] as Anbu\n* [[Ramesh Thilak]]\n* Soundarya Bala Nandakumar as Pub Singer\n* Vittal Prasad\n* Darkey as singer in \"Ulagam Oruvanukka\" Song\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nIn June 2015, director [[Pa. Ranjith]] announced his third directorial venture, which would follow his previous two films ''[[Attakathi]]'' (2012) and ''[[Madras (film)|Madras]]'' (2014), with [[Rajinikanth]] via [[Twitter]]. Rajinikanth had been impressed with Ranjith's work in ''[[Madras (film)|Madras]]'' (2014) and subsequently Rajinikanth's daughter, [[Soundarya Rajinikanth|Soundarya]], asked Ranjith to work on a script for her father.<ref name=\"appa\">{{cite news|last1=Srinivas|first1=Ramanujam|title=Appa and I|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/soundarya-rajinikanth-on-her-father/article8741614.ece?secpage=true&secname=entertainment|accessdate=17 July 2016|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=17 July 2016|location=[[Chennai]]}}</ref> Working with Ranjith would make ''Kabali'' Rajinikanth's first film with a novel director for the first time since his collaboration with [[S. Shankar]] in ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"The Hindu 2\">{{cite news|last1=Ramanujam|first1=Srinivasa|title=Rajinikanth is changing... and here's why|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/rajinikanth-is-changingand-heres-why/article7275306.ece|accessdate=22 August 2015|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 June 2015}}</ref> In an interview with ''IndiaGlitz'', producer [[S. Thanu]] revealed that Rajinikanth had personally asked him to produce the Ranjith-directed film. The producer's commercially successful ''[[Bairavi]]'' (1978) was Rajinikanth's first lead role film and the two had not collaborated since.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz 1\">{{cite web|title=Rajini asked me to produce his next : Kalaipuli S Thanu Interview|language=Tamil|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajini-asked-me-to-produce-his-next--kalaipuli-s-thanu-interview-hindi-videos-60094.html|format=video|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> It was speculated that Rajinikanth's role would be based on a real-life mob boss from [[Chennai]].<ref name=\"Business Standard 1\">{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's next film loosely based on real-life don|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/rajinikanth-s-next-film-loosely-based-on-real-life-don-115081501802_1.html|accessdate=22 August 2015|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|work=[[Business Standard]]|date=15 August 2015}}</ref> [[Santhosh Narayanan]] was confirmed as the film's music composer, continuing his partnership with Ranjith after the latter's previous two films. Ranjith also retained G. Murali, the cinematographer of ''Madras''.\n\nOn 17 August 2015, Ranjith announced the title of the film to be ''Kabali'' and that Rajinikanth would play the role of Kabaliswaran.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz 2\">{{cite web|title=Here is the confirmation on Rajini-Ranjith film title|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/140042.html|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015|ref= |date=17 August 2015}}</ref> The makers of the film had earlier considered using title ''Kaali'', which was the title of [[Kaali (1980 film)|Rajinikanth's 1980 film]]. As that film did not do well in the Tamil Nadu box office at the time, the makers passed on using it for the new film. Another title, ''Kannabhiran'', was also considered but it was later found that the title's rights were already held by director [[Ameer Sultan]] for a future film.<ref name=\"Indiglitz 3\">{{cite web|title=New title for Rajini-Raniith film?|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/140001.html|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015|ref= |date=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn the film, [[Rajinikanth]] plays the role of an aged crime boss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' teaser unveiled, watch the superstar in a new gangster avatar|url=http://www.abplive.in/movies/rajinikanths-kabali-teaser-unveiled-watch-the-superstar-in-a-new-gangster-avatar-333752|publisher=ABP Live|date=2 May 2016}}</ref> According to the Telugu newspaper ''[[Eenadu]]'', Rajinikanth, after being impressed with ''[[Nayakan]]'' (1987), requested its director [[Mani Ratnam]] to write a similar script, but the project never materialised; its similarities with Ranjith's script for ''Kabali'' made him accept to star in the latter film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.eenadu.net/pdf/2016/07/21/20160721a_010135003.jpg |title=\u0c30\u0c1c\u0c3f\u0c28\u0c40 \u0c2e\u0c47\u0c28\u0c3f\u0c2f\u0c3e... \u0c07\u0c02\u0c24\u0c3f\u0c02\u0c24 \u0c15\u0c3e\u0c26\u0c2f\u0c3e! |work=[[Eenadu]] |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016 |trans-title=Rajini's mania... is unrestrained! |language=Telugu |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721071017/http://epaper.eenadu.net/pdf/2016/07/21/20160721a_010135003.jpg |archivedate=21 July 2016 |df= }}</ref> [[Dinesh Ravi]], who played the lead in Ranjith's ''[[Attakathi]]'' (2012), and [[Kalaiyarasan]], who played pivotal roles in both of the director's previous films, were also confirmed to be part of the film. An important role was offered to [[Prakash Raj]] initially,<ref name=\"Timyes of India 1\">{{cite news|last1=Balachandran|first1=Logesh|title=Prakash Raj in Rajinikanth-Ranjith film|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Prakash-Raj-in-Rajinikanth-Ranjith-film/articleshow/47733666.cms|accessdate=22 August 2015|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=20 June 2015}}</ref> but later it was said that the role was declined due to scheduling issues and [[John Vijay]] was cast for the role instead.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mrinalini|first1=Sundar|title=I play an educated conman in Veera Sivaji|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/I-play-an-educated-conman-in-Veera-Sivaji/articleshow/50256074.cms|website=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=31 December 2015|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> It was later confirmed that the role of the lead character's wife would be given to [[Radhika Apte]], who was introduced to Tamil films through ''[[Dhoni (film)|Dhoni]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"Filmibeat 1\">{{cite news|last1=Gopinath|first1=Avinash|title=Dhaniskaa bags a role in Rajinikanth's next|url=http://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/news/2015/confirmed-radhika-apte-is-rajinikanth-s-heroine-in-pa-ranjith-s-project-192040.html|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|publisher=[[Oneindia|Filmibeat]]|date=10 August 2015|accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> [[Dhansika]] was signed to play a supporting character in the film.<ref name=\"IBN 1\">{{cite news|title=Dhaniskaa bags a role in Rajinikanth's next|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dhaniskaa-bags-a-role-in-rajinikanths-next-film-1035018.html|accessdate=22 August 2015|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|publisher=[[CNN-IBN|IBN]]|date=10 August 2015}}</ref> Soundarya Nandakumar, a television actress best known for her participation in [[Star Vijay]]'s ''[[Airtel Super Singer 3]]'', was chosen for a cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/Film-projectors-New-age-of-film-promotions/2016/07/16/article3529323.ece|title=Film projectors: New age of film promotions|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nOn 18 August 2015, director Pa Ranjith announced on his [[Twitter]] page that [[principal photography]] would begin the following week,<ref name=\"New India Express 08-18-15\">{{cite news|title=Rajini's Next with Ranjith Titled Kabali!|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Rajinis-Next-with-Ranjith-Titled-Kabali/2015/08/18/article2979353.ece|accessdate=24 August 2015|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=18 August 2015}}</ref> which was confirmed on 22 August when ''Behindwoods'' covered a [[photo shoot]] which took place on 21 August at [[AVM Studios]] in [[Chennai]]. First schedule of the filming started on [[Vinayagar Chaturthi]] on 17 September 2015 at the Russian Centre of Science and Cultural in Chennai.<ref name=\"Behindwoods 09-18-15\">{{cite news|last1=Saravanakumar|title=Superstar Rajni's Kabali first day shooting...|URL=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/rajinikanth-appears-stylish-in-the-first-look-poster-of-kabali.html|publisher=Behindwoods|date=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Kabali (soundtrack)\n}}\n[[Santhosh Narayanan]] composed the film's soundtrack and background score of the film. This is the first time, he is scoring for a Rajini-starrer film. The soundtrack album features five songs with lyrics written by [[Kabilan (lyricist)|Kabilan]], [[Vivek (lyricist)|Vivek]], Umadevi and [[Arunraja Kamaraj]] and one song was released as a bonus track after the film's release. The audio rights were acquired by [[Think Music India|Think Music]] and the soundtrack album was released on 12 June 2016 in both original Tamil and [[Hindi]] versions, the [[Telugu language|Telugu]] version was released on 26 June 2016, whereas the [[Malay language|Malay]] version consists of two songs was released on 1 July 2016. A bonus track was released on 5 August 2016. The background score was released on 14 August 2016.\n\n== Release ==\n''Kabali'' was released in Tamil worldwide, along with [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] versions in [[Hindi]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], and [[Malay language|Malay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-rajinikanth-kabali-records-shattered-332602|title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' has many feats before the release; know all records it shattered|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=3 June 2016}}</ref> The film was scheduled to be released simultaneously in Singapore and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajinikanths-kabali-to-be-released-in-malay/article8631637.ece|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali to be released in Malay|date=22 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Malik Streams Productions and Distribution, a Malaysian media company, will simultaneously release the film in Malay for exclusive screening in Malaysia alongside the original Tamil version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaivision.com/kabali-tamil-movie-dubbed-malay/|title=Kabali Tamil movie to be dubbed in Malay|last=|first=|date=23 May 2016|website=chennaivision|publisher=chennaivision|access-date=2 June 2016}}</ref> The film was also dubbed in Mandarin<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-36852789 |title = Kabali: How Rajinikanth still packs a punch|work = BBC News|date = 23 July 2016|last1 = Tilak|first1 = Sudha G.}}</ref> and Thai, and was released in Hong Kong, China and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/06/01/rajinikanth-kabali_n_10233732.html|title=Rajinikanth's Upcoming 'Kabali' Is The Hottest Indian Film In The Trade Right Now|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"music\">{{cite news|last1=J|first1=Sam Daniel Stalin|title=From Kabali Makers, a Musical Treat For Rajinikanth's Family|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/from-kabali-makers-a-musical-treat-for-rajinikanths-family-1418090|accessdate=17 July 2016|work=[[NDTV]]|date=12 June 2016|location=[[Chennai]]}}</ref>\n''Kabali'' also premiered at the [[Le Grand Rex]] in Paris, France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaivision.com/kabali-premiered-paris-le-grand-rex/|title=Kabali to be premiered at Paris' Le Grand Rex|date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/261216/kabali-goes-to-thailand.html |title = Kabali goes to Thailand|date = 25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\n[[File:Kabali Flight.jpg|thumb|An [[Airbus A320]] of [[AirAsia India]] [[Wrap advertising|wrapped]], featuring [[Rajinikanth]]]]\nAfter the airline [[AirAsia India]] became an official partner for ''Kabali'', an [[Airbus A320]] owned by the airline was [[wrap advertising|wrapped]] with the film's title and an image of [[Rajinikanth]] depicted as Kabaleeshwaran.<ref name=\"music\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajinikanth-radhika-apte-kabali-official-airline-partner-air-asia-tamil-news-160712.html|title=IndiaGlitz&nbsp;\u2014 Rajinikanth Radhika Apte Kabali official airline partner Air Asia&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=10 June 2016}}</ref> It was the first time a passenger jet had been wrapped for advertising an Indian film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/catalyst/for-these-brands-the-sky-is-the-limit/article8880735.ece|title=For these brands, the sky is the limit|date=21 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> The Indian financial company [[Muthoot Pappachan Group|Muthoot FinCorp]] who is also an official partner of the film produced silver coins embossed with the image of actor as cast in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/business/news/Muthoot-Fincorp-to-offer-silver-coins-on-Kabali/2016/07/14/article3529254.ece|title=Muthoot Fincorp to offer silver coins on 'Kabali' |publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/muthoot-pappachan-group-joins-kabali-mania-issues-silver-coins-with-rajinikanth-image/article8849696.ece|title=Muthoot joins Kabali mania; issues silver coins with Rajinikanth image |publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> Its [[Teaser campaign|teaser trailer]] was released in April 2016 and went viral in Asia and gained 5 million views in less than 24 hours becoming the most viewed teaser in Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-rajinikanth-kabali-teaser-video-326886|title=Watch: Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' teaser unveiled; crosses 1.5 million views within one day|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatandhra.com/movies/movie-news/kabali-becomes-highest-viewed-teaser-in-asia-74853.html|title=Kabali Becomes Highest Viewed Teaser In Asia|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Online piracy issue ===\nOn 19 July 2016, three days prior to the film's worldwide release, it was reported that pirated copies of the film were leaked online in [[darknet]].<ref name=\"IBT\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-kabali-full-movie-leaked-online-download-report-687091 | title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' full movie leaked online for download: Report | website=International Business Times | date=19 July 2016 | accessdate=19 July 2016 | author=Hooli, Shekhar H}}</ref> ''[[The Indian Express]]'' reported that although the leaked copies were available only in the darknet, lots of fake links were being circulated in the web. The makers of the film had approached [[Madras High Court]] in anticipation of piracy and had requested the authority to ensure that it does not happen.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/kabali-rajinikanth-leaks-online-three-days-before-release-2922918/ | title=Rajinikanth's Kabali leaks online three days before release | newspaper=The Indian Express | date=19 July 2016 | accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> [[Central Board for Film Certification|CBFC]] chief [[Pahlaj Nihalani]] commented on the issue by saying that the leak had nothing to do with his office in Mumbai and reiterated the fact that Kabali, a Tamil film, was certified by [[Central Board of Film Certification|CBFC]]'s Chennai office. He also added that the leak would not have much effect on the film's [[box office]] collection.\n\nTwo days later, on 21 July 2016, a two-minute long sequence of the film was also leaked online, which subsequently went [[viral video|viral]] on instant messaging app, [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=\"FP-WA\">{{cite news | url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-opening-scene-leaked-on-whatsapp-rajinikanth-film-said-to-be-out-on-dark-web-2906084.html | title='Kabali' opening scene leaked on Whatsapp; Rajinikanth film said to be 'out' on dark web | work=Firstpost | date=21 July 2016 | accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> Commenting on the leak, producer Kalaippuli S Thanu said, \"Watching Thalaivar entry on phone or computer won't give you goosebumps. Say thank you to pirates, let's watch it in theaters from Friday\" through his [[Twitter]] account. ''[[The News Minute]]'' reported that the sequence leak, which carried English as well as Arabic subtitles, could have been released from Gulf countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intro-scene-kabali-leaked-outrage-online-producer-says-watch-it-theatres-46855 | title=Intro scene of Kabali leaked! Outrage online, producer says watch it in theatres | publisher=[[The News Minute]] | date=21 July 2016 | accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's release, a partial copy which had been filmed with a mobile phone in a cinema was posted to [[Vimeo]], but was subsequently removed from the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/07/23/record-debuts-for-tamil-superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-as-producer-discusses-piracy-and-a-sequel|title=Record Debuts For Tamil Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' As Producer Discusses Piracy And A Sequel}}</ref>\n\n=== Alternate ending ===\nThe Malaysian version of the film proceeds beyond the fade to black and offers a concrete ending, stating that Kabali surrendered to the police. This alternate ending was created at the behest of [[Film Censorship Board of Malaysia]], which does not allow showcasing of policemen encouraging violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kabali: Rajinikanth fans witnessed an alternate ending in Malaysian cinemas?|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Kabali-Rajinikanth-fans-witnessed-an-alternate-endingin-Malaysian-cinemas/articleshow/53365772.cms|accessdate=26 July 2016|agency=[[Times News Network|TNN]]|newspaper=The Times of India|date=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali to have different ending in Malaysia|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/rajinikanth-kabali-ending-malaysia-2934856/|accessdate=26 July 2016|agency=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LPF confirmed 'Kabali' to have different ending in Malaysia|url=http://www.themalaysiantimes.com.my/lpf-confirmed-kabali-to-have-different-ending-in-malaysia/|accessdate=26 July 2016|publisher=The Malaysian Times|date=24 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n''Kabali'' was a highly anticipated film throughout the country, including cities like  Chennai,Bangalore, Mumbai, and Hyderabad, but the film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/220716/kabali-movie-review-slow-burner-without-much-respite.html|title=Kabali movie review: Slow-burner without much respite}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/220716/kabali-fever-takes-over-chennai-mumbai-and-bengaluru-fans-watch-5am-show.html|title=Deccanchronicle}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-review-rajinikanth-film-garners-mixed-response-telugu-audience-687491|title=ibtimes|date=22 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.sg/kabali-gets-mixed-reviews-will-this-affect-malay-version-rajinikanths-film-2438|title='Kabali' gets mixed reviews; will this have some impact on its Malay version?|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n''IndiaGlitz'' rated the film 3 out of 5 and called it \"A very different Rajinikanth Experience\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kabali-tamil-movie-review-19903.html|title=Kabali review. Kabali Tamil movie review, story, rating&nbsp;\u2014 IndiaGlitz.com|website=IndiaGlitz|access-date=23 July 2016}}</ref> Behindwoods rated the film 2.75 out of 5 and stated that <nowiki>''Rajinikanth in a different dimension,but Kabali might not work for everyone''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/kabali/kabali-review.html|title=Kabali (aka) Kabaali review|website=Behindwoods|access-date=24 July 2016|date=22 July 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Indian Express]]'' rated the movie 3.5 out of 5 and said that,<nowiki>''Rajinikanth's film lacks pace and mass''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/kabali-quick-review-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-2928869/|title=Kabali quick review: Rajinikanth's film lacks pace and mass|date=22 July 2016|access-date=24 July 2016}}</ref> ''Filmibeat'' rated the movie 3 out of 5 stars and stated that <nowiki>''You might be disappointed if you go into the cinema hall keeping in mind the recent hype and hoopla around Kabali\". However, this is definitely Rajinikanth's best in the recent times''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/reviews/2016/kabali-movie-review-rating-story-rajinikanth-s-show-with-a-difference-234608.html|title='Kabali' Movie Review & Rating: A Decent Drama Sans Superstardom!|date=21 July 2016|access-date=28 July 2016}}</ref>  ''International Business Times'' rated the film 3.5 out of 5, stating \"Rajnikanth shines in politically charged movie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/kabali-review-rajnikanth-shines-politically-charged-movie-1572019|title=Kabali review: Rajnikanth shines in politically charged movie|date=22 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Baradwaj Rangan of ''[[The Hindu]]'' wrote \"Ranjith\u2019s filmmaking is different too, and not in a good way. Kabali does have some of his trademarks...but the life that infused his earlier films is missing.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rangan |first1=Baradwaj |title=Kabali: An unsatisfying clash between the impulses of star and director |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/Kabali-An-unsatisfying-clash-between-the-impulses-of-star-and-director/article14515117.ece |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=22 July 2016 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 70% based on 10 reviews, with an average rating of 6.4/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kabali/|title=Kabali (2016)}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=There is insufficient context for readers unfamiliar with Indian castes to understand exactly what the controversy is. Are there laws that are being broken? Specifics are missing.}}\nSome reviewers attacked the movie for portraying Rajinikanth as a dalit leader. The film was targeted for depicting [[Dalit]] caste which the whole team refused to accept.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/kabali-rajinikanth-movie-review-radhika-apte-dalit-script-2928624/|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali: Backroom script of movie has a Dalit subtext|date=22 July 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-director-pa-ranjith-rajinikanth-approved-politics-dialogue-rhetoric-in-film-2920124.html|title=Kabali director Pa Ranjith: 'Rajinikanth approved politics, dialogue, rhetoric in film' \u2013 Firstpost|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=Firstpost|language=en-US|access-date=6 November 2016}}</ref> However, some dalit outfits referred it as a Dalit movie.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thereel.scroll.in/812882/kabali-film-is-a-response-to-the-2012-dharmapuri-caste-riots-says-dalit-scholar-stalin-rajangam|title='Kabali' film is a response to the 2012 Dharmapuri caste riots, says Dalit scholar Stalin Rajangam|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|newspaper=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/In-Kabali-Dalits-see-a-natty-redeemer/articleshow/53347858.cms|title=In Kabali, Dalits see a natty redeemer&nbsp;\u2014 Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Box office ==\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=Section, which should focus on box office performance, i.e. gross figures, mixes in nett figures. This creates a confusing overview of how the film performed compared to other films which only focus on gross receipts. See [[MOS:FILM]].}}\n''Kabali'' had the highest worldwide opening day for a South Indian film, surpassing the record set by ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning]]'' by earning {{INRConvert|875|m}} on the first day.<ref name=\"International Business Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964 |title='Kabali' Box Office collection |work=International Business Times India|date=4 August 2016}}</ref> The film also had the highest 3-day opening weekend for an Indian film surpassing the {{INRConvert|2.06|b}} record set by ''[[Sultan (2016 film)|Sultan]]'' two weeks earlier as it earned {{INRConvert|2.11|b}}.<ref name=\"International Business Times\" />\n\n=== Disputed gross figures ===\nBox office gross values of {{INR}}6\u20136.75 billion were reported in the first 13 days by several organisations including ''Financial Express'' and ''Indian Express'',<ref name=\"Financial Express 650 crore 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/334390/kabali-box-office-collections-at-over-rs-650-cr-rajinikanth-starrer-is-now-no-1-movie-in-india/4/|title=Rajinikanth starrer Kabali box office collections rise to over Rs 650 crore, turns No. 1 movie in India&nbsp;\u2014 The Financial Express|date=1 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Financial Express 650 crore 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/334390/kabali-box-office-collections-at-over-rs-650-cr-rajinikanth-starrer-is-now-no-1-movie-in-india/3/|title=Rajinikanth starrer Kabali box office collections rise to over Rs 650 crore, turns No. 1 movie in India&nbsp;\u2014 The Financial Express|date=1 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> which were more than double the estimates made by other sources.<ref name=\"IBT 675 questioned\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|title='Kabali' box office collection: Reports of Rajinikanth-starrer raking in Rs. 675 crore in 13 days are fake|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805214307/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|archivedate=5 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' (IBT) and ''[[Firstpost]]'' criticised these estimates as inflated, explaining the discrepancy as due in part to the addition of \"pre-release business\" figures, such as music and satellite rights sales of {{INR}}2 billion,<ref name=\"Firstpost 600 questioned\" /> being factored into the box office sales totals.<ref name=\"IBT 675 questioned\" /> ''Firstpost'' wrote, \"More conservative estimates put Kabali\u2019s collections at around Rs [3 billion] from worldwide ticket sales.\"<ref name=\"Firstpost 600 questioned\">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/rajinikanth-kabali-has-earned-rs-600-crore-at-the-global-box-office-or-has-it-2932578.html|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali has earned Rs 600 crore at the global box office. Or has it? - Firstpost|date=3 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>  IBT's analysts in August 2016 estimated the film's worldwide gross total of its first 13 days at around {{INRConvert|3.5|b}}.<ref name=\"IBT 350 crore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964 |title='Kabali' Box Office collection |work=International Business Times India|date=4 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805071102/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964|archivedate=5 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFigures given in December 2016 by ''Financial Express'' indicated an estimated domestic gross of {{INR}}215 crore and an international gross of {{INR}}262 crore, for a worldwide total of {{INR}}477 crore.<ref name=\"IE Dec 2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-birthday-today-as-superstar-rajni-turns-65-wishes-pour-in/471636/|title=Rajinikanth birthday today; As superstar Rajni turns 65, wishes pour&nbsp;in|date=12 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> A figure of US$77 million given by Rob Cain in May 2017 converted to approximately {{INR}}493\u2013499 crore.<!--Method: {{INRConvert|494|c|year=2016}} NOTE: Since the Cain source doesn't mention a specific INR value, and is presumably using 2017 US dollars to talk about the gross of a 2016 Indian film, we're forced to extrapolate a range of INR values under 500. --><ref name=\"Forbes 77 mil USD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/05/11/armies-of-ajith-fans-mobilize-to-blast-vivegam-teaser-to-record-views/|title=Armies Of Ajith Fans Mobilize To Blast 'Vivegam' Teaser To Record Views|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017|quote=Kabali, which starred blockbuster hero Rajinikanth, went on to gross nearly 5 billion rupees ($77 million) worldwide, making it the 6th highest grossing Indian film in history at the time.}}</ref> According to ''International Business Times'' in October 2017, ''Kabali''{{'}}s final worldwide gross was around {{INRConvert|286|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Upadhyaya|first1=Prakash|title=Mersal box office collection: A crowning-moment for Vijay as his film joins Rs 200-crore club|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/mersal-12-days-box-office-collection-crowning-vijay-film-joins-rs-200-crore-club-2nd-weekend-747432|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=30 October 2017|language=en}}</ref> According to [[Box Office India]], the film's final worldwide gross was {{INRConvert|305|c}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=2.0: All India - Overseas - Worldwide Update|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=4486|work=[[Box Office India]]|date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n''Kabali'' had the highest opening day for a South Indian film in terms of gross revenue, grossing {{INRConvert|530|m}} on the first day of its release in India from all the languages and was just behind the 2015 film ''[[Prem Ratan Dhan Payo]]'' for the highest first day gross in India in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2179|title=Top Openings India&nbsp;\u2014 All Films All Languages|website=Box Office India|date=24 July 2016}}</ref> It also became the first Tamil film to gross {{INRConvert|200|m}} in a single day from Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-box-office-collections-superstar-rajinikanth-2910850.html|title=Kabali box office collections: Let's do the math on Rajinikanth-starrer's numbers|work=[[Firstpost]]}}</ref> ''Kabali'' went on to record the top-earning first weekend in India, grossing {{INRConvert|1.2425|b}} in three days from all its versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2186|title=Salman Khan Has Top Three Domestic Weekends&nbsp;\u2014 Kabali 7th&nbsp;\u2014 Box Office India|work=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2185|title=Kabali Breaks Weekend NETT Collection Record Of Sultan&nbsp;\u2014 Box Office India|work=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> ''International Business Times'' stated on 4 August 2016 that ''Kabali'' grossed {{INRConvert|2.05|b}} domestically in ten days,<ref name=\"ibtimes.co.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|title='Kabali' Box Office Collection Reports|work=International Business Times|date=4 August 2016}}</ref> before later stating on 9 August 2016 that it grossed {{INRConvert|1.96|b}} domestically in seventeen days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-17-days-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-film-moving-towards-rs-200-crore-mark-india-689371|title='Kabali' 17 days box office collection: Rajinikanth's film moving towards Rs. 200 crore mark in India|first=Prakash|last=Upadhyaya|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Overseas ===\n''Kabali'' grossed US$15.70 million ({{INR}}105 crore) till its tenth day.<ref name=\"International Business Times\" /> The film had earned US$11.20 million ({{INR}}75.27 crore) in its first four-day weekend overseas,<ref name=\"Kabali Overseas BoxOffice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-overseas-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-flick-mints-rs-105-crore-690034|title=Kabali Overseas BoxOffice|publisher=ibtimes|date=16 August 2016}}</ref> breaking the record previously held by ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (US$10.32 million) as the highest-grossing first weekend for an Indian film in overseas markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/box-office/special-features/id/748|title=Box Office: Overseas collections of Rajinikanth's Kabali|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|date=23 July 2016}}</ref> According to ''International Business Times'' in May 2017, the film's final overseas gross was US$15.65&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hooli|first=Shekhar|title=Baahubali 2 overseas box office collection: Rajamouli's film beats Chennai Express, Kabali's lifetime record in 1st weekend|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-overseas-box-office-collection-rajamoulis-film-beats-chennai-express-kabalis-725036|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=1 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Kabali (film)}}\n\n== Sequel ==\nShortly after the film's success, in an interview with Don Groves, S. Thanu said that the initial results exceeded his expectations and that the film's ending sets up a sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/07/23/record-debuts-for-tamil-superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-as-producer-discusses-piracy-and-a-sequel/|title=Record Debuts For Tamil Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' As Producer Discusses Piracy And A Sequel|work=Forbes|date=23 July 2016|access-date=31 July 2016}}</ref> On 25 July 2016, he spoke, \"We created an open climax for ''Kabali''. So, director Ranjith and I are interested in a sequel for this gangster flick. However, Rajinikanth will have to give us the nod to carry on. The film\u2019s collections indicate that it is a sensational hit, and has surpassed all records\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/250716/i-am-ready-for-kabali-sequel-kalaipuli-s-thanu.html|title= I am ready for Kabali sequel: Kalaipuli S Thanu |work=Deccan Chronicle|date=25 July 2016|access-date=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe song \"Neruppu Da\" inspired a 2017 film of [[Neruppu Da|same name]] starring [[Vikram Prabhu]]. The title was kept as the film portrayed Vikram Prabhu as firefighter and a fan of Rajinikanth.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.catchnews.com/regional-cinema/vikram-prabhu-turns-producer-with-neruppu-da-a-film-titled-after-kabali-s-song-vikram-pabhu-to-play-rajinikanth-fan-in-neruppu-da-song-1467805906.html |title = Why did Vikram Prabhu copy the title of Kabali's song, Nerrupu da for his maiden production?}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|5071886|Kabali}}\n* {{mojo title|kabali}}\n{{Pa. Ranjith}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime action films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Santhosh Narayanan]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian gangster films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime action films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 film directed by Pa. Ranjith}}\n{{Redirect|Kabali|the village in Turkey|Kabal\u0131, Vezirk\u00f6pr\u00fc}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kabali\n| image          = Kabali poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Pa. Ranjith]]\n| producer       = [[Kalaipuli S. Thanu]]\n| writer         = Pa. Ranjith\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Rajinikanth]]\n* [[Radhika Apte]]\n* [[Sai Dhanshika]]\n* [[Winston Chao]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Santhosh Narayanan]]\n| cinematography = [[Murali G]]\n| editing        = [[Praveen K. L.|Praveen K.L]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Editor Praveen KL's hint about the Teaser release of 'Kabali'??|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/editor-praveen-kl-starts-working-on-superstar-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-kabali-tamil-news-153814.html|website=Indiaglitz|publisher=Indiaglitz|accessdate=15 July 2016|date=March 2016}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[S. Thanu|V Creations]]\n| distributor    = {{ubl|[[Gemini Film Circuit]]|[[Maxlab Cinemas and Entertainments]]|[[Fox Star Studios]]|Malik Stream Corporations}}\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|2016|07|21|[[Malaysia]]|ref1=<ref name = BWAnj>{{cite web|url=http://www.catchnews.com/regional-cinema/rajinikanth-starrer-kabali-s-first-premiere-to-be-held-in-malaysia-here-are-the-complete-details-rajinikanth-kabali-movie-latest-news-1467726038.html|title = Rajinikanth starrer Kabali's first premiere to be held in Malaysia. |publisher=Catch News|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016}}</ref>|2016|07|22|Worldwide}}\n| runtime        = 152 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/superstar-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-dhanshika-kabali-censor-u-certificate-run-time-tamil-news-162995.html|title=Kabali:censor and running time detail|date=11 July 2016|access-date=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{Estimation}} {{INR|100 [[crore]]}}<ref name=\"Kabali\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-1st-day-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-film-strikes-gold-its-opening-day-687566|title='Kabali' 1st day collection at box office: Rajinikanth's film beats first day records of 'Vedalam' to become biggest opener in TN|date=23 July 2016|work=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = Disputed (see [[#Disputed gross figures|box office]])\n}}\n\n'''''Kabali''''' is a 2016 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[Action film|action]] [[crime film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=kabali.htm|title=Kabali (2016)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/kabali-2016|title=KABALI|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]}}</ref> written and directed by [[Pa. Ranjith]] and produced by [[S. Thanu|Kalaipuli S. Thanu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kabali-the-album-of-rajinikanths-film-will-be-launched-on-june-11/1/683230.html|title=Kabali: Music album of Rajinikanths gangster film to be launched on June 11|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> The film plot concerns the gang war between Kabaleeswaran (played by [[Rajinikanth]]) and Tony Lee (portrayed by [[Winston Chao]]). [[Radhika Apte]], [[Sai Dhanshika]], [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]], [[Dinesh Ravi|Dinesh]], [[Kalaiyarasan]], and [[John Vijay]] also appear in pivotal roles.\n\nPrincipal photography for the film began on 21 August 2015 in [[Chennai]]. While filming mostly occurred in [[Malaysia]], some scenes were shot in [[Bangkok]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioadhurs.nz/album/kabali/|title=Kabali (2016)|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in Tamil along with dubbed versions in Telugu and Hindi on 22 July 2016, while the film was released in Malay a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/kabali-malay-version-to-release-on-july-29-news-tamil-qhekPIdgacdcd.html|title='Kabali' Malay version to release on July 29|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"HTDelayFilmDate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/makers-launch-kabali-app-even-as-its-release-is-delayed-by-two-weeks/story-XuGJEknDjIuvmLZHQtr6CI.html|title=Makers launch Kabali app even as its release is delayed by two weeks|date=11 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-releases-sends-fans-into-frenzy-from-4-a-m/articleshow/53331557.cms|title=Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' releases, sends fans into frenzy from 4 a.m&nbsp;\u2014 The Economic Times|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> ''Kabali'' was released on 3200 screens in [[India]], of which 2200 were in [[South India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2176|title=Kabali (Hindi) And Madaari First Day Business 2200 1000 3200}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!--This plot summary refers to the general version of the film and not the Malaysian one-->\nA [[Kuala Lumpur]]\u2013based [[Crime boss|don]] Kabaleeswaran alias Kabali is released after spending 25 years in prison on a false charge of starting a massacre at a local [[Hindu]] temple that killed many, including his wife Kumudhavalli. He immediately resumes charge of his old gang and soon confronts Loganathan, a [[drug smuggling|drug smuggler]]. Loga insults Kumudha, saying that she would have been sold into prostitution had she been alive. In retaliation, Kabali rams his car into Loga, killing him; however, the incident makes him believe that his wife may be still alive. Later, Kabali survives an assassination attempt by Tamizh Kumaran alias Kumaran, whose father Tamilmaaran was killed by Kabali when Kumaran was a young boy. The next day, at a function organised by the Free Life Foundation School, a school started by Kabali's friend Ameer to reform youngsters involved in criminal activities, Kabali talks about his past.\n\nKabali was the protege of Tamilmaaran's father Tamilnesan, a don who fought for the rights of [[Tamil Malaysians]]. Tamilnesan was killed by Veerasekaran, a member of his gang who disliked his rules such as not involving in illegal activities like drug smuggling and prostitution. Following Tamilnesan's death, Kabali took charge of Tamilnesan's gang. Veera manipulated Tamilmaaran by telling him that he, being Tamilnesan's son, should lead the gang and not Kabali. Tamilmaaran invited Kabali and a pregnant Kumudha for a temple function. However, this was revealed to be a trap as Veera and his men confronted Kabali and Kumudha at the function. In the ensuing scuffle, Kabali was brutally attacked while Kumudha was shot and seemingly killed. Kabali then killed Tamilmaaran for his betrayal in front of a young Kumaran and was soon arrested on a false charge of instigating the massacre.\n\nKumaran, after hearing Kabali's speech, realises his mistake and apologises to him. He tells him that Velu, one of Veera's henchmen who was present at the temple massacre, is aware of what happened to Kumudha. Kabali then leaves for [[Thailand]], where Velu is residing. On confronting Velu, he learns that his daughter is still alive. At this juncture, Kabali is confronted by Yogi, a [[contract killing|contract killer]] hired by Veera and his boss Tony Lee, who heads the rival Gang 43 in Kuala Lumpur, to eliminate Kabali. Yogi instead kills the men who had come with her and reveals herself to Kabali as his daughter, who had been raised by Velu. She also tells him that Kumudha is still alive and is living with a French family in [[Pondicherry|Puducherry]]. Kabali and Yogi then leave for Puducherry, where, after several days of searching, they reunite with Kumudha and spend a few days with her there. While in Puducherry, Kabali and his family are attacked by men sent by Tony. However, Kabali and Yogi fight them off and escape safely with Kumudha.\n\nKabali and his family soon return to Kuala Lumpur, where he is told that Ameer has been severely injured in a car accident set up by Tony; his henchman Jeeva was brutally chopped to pieces by Tony after refusing to join Gang 43; and Gang 43 had destroyed the Free Life Foundation School and started to control the Kuala Lumpur underworld, eliminating any gang who dared to oppose them. On hearing all this, Kabali decides to finish Veera and Tony. He and his family attend the 100th birthday party for a respected Malaysian don Ang Lee, who had invited all gangs, including Gang 43. At the party, Kabali starts a shootout with the help of Kumaran, which ends with him killing Veera and Tony.\n\nSome months later, Kabali, Kumudha, Kumaran, and Yogi attend a function organised by the Free Life Foundation. One of the Free Life alumni, a youngster named Tiger, who is known to be aggressive and reckless, walks up to Kabali, with scenes showing him speaking to the police prior to the function. The screen cuts to black, and the sound of a gun clicking and a gunshot afterwards is heard.<!--do ''not'' write that the film ends ambiguously as it may show POV-->\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Kabaliswaran (Kabali), the head of Malaysian Gangster group '00'.\n* [[Radhika Apte]] as Kumudhavalli Kabaliswaran, Kabali's wife\n* [[Sai Dhanshika]] as Yogitha Kabaleeswaran, Kabali's daughter who is a contract killer in Thailand.\n* [[Winston Chao]] as Tony Lee, industrialist, businessman and a head of Malaysian Gangster group '43'.\n* [[Kishore (actor)|Kishore]] as Veerasekaran, the second head of '43'\n* [[Attakathi Dinesh|Dinesh]] as Jeeva, Kabali's gang member.\n* [[Kalaiyarasan]] as Thamizh Kumaran (Kumaran), Tamizh Nesan's grandson and Tamizh Maran's son. He is a teacher in Kabali's school.\n* [[John Vijay]] as Ameer, Kabali's sidekick/trusted aide.\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Tamizh Nesan, the founder of '00' to protect Malaysian Tamizhans(Guest Appearence)\n* [[Riythvika]] as Meena, a drug-addicted girl who joins Kabali's school for a reason to safe from drugs. Later, Kabali adopts her as his daughter.\n* [[Sangili Murugan]] as Palace Owner\n* [[Rosyam Nor]] as Tony's sidekick\n* [[Charles Vinoth]] as Tamizh Maaran, Tamizha Nesan's son and Kabali's best friend.\n* [[Mime Gopi]] as Loganathan, '43' second main member to do drug supply.\n* [[R. Amarendran]] as Velu/Venu, Veera's henchman.\n* Lishesh as Seeni, '43' main member to do money laundry.\n* [[Kabali Vishwanth|Visvanth]] as Jai\n* Hari Krishnan as Tiger, school student who encounters Kabali in the end.\n* Gajaraj as Marthandam, Kabali's teammate in young age but later works for Gang '43'.\n* Sampath Ram as Sampath, Kabali's teammate.\n* [[Rama (actress)|Rama]] as Mallika\n* [[Uday Mahesh]] as Durai\n* [[Poster Nandakumar|Nandakumar]] as Anbu\n* [[Ramesh Thilak]]\n* Soundarya Bala Nandakumar as Pub Singer\n* Vittal Prasad\n* Darkey as singer in \"Ulagam Oruvanukka\" Song\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nIn June 2015, director [[Pa. Ranjith]] announced his third directorial venture, which would follow his previous two films ''[[Attakathi]]'' (2012) and ''[[Madras (film)|Madras]]'' (2014), with [[Rajinikanth]] via [[Twitter]]. Rajinikanth had been impressed with Ranjith's work in ''[[Madras (film)|Madras]]'' (2014) and subsequently Rajinikanth's daughter, [[Soundarya Rajinikanth|Soundarya]], asked Ranjith to work on a script for her father.<ref name=\"appa\">{{cite news|last1=Srinivas|first1=Ramanujam|title=Appa and I|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/soundarya-rajinikanth-on-her-father/article8741614.ece?secpage=true&secname=entertainment|accessdate=17 July 2016|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=17 July 2016|location=[[Chennai]]}}</ref> Working with Ranjith would make ''Kabali'' Rajinikanth's first film with a novel director for the first time since his collaboration with [[S. Shankar]] in ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"The Hindu 2\">{{cite news|last1=Ramanujam|first1=Srinivasa|title=Rajinikanth is changing... and here's why|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/rajinikanth-is-changingand-heres-why/article7275306.ece|accessdate=22 August 2015|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=2 June 2015}}</ref> In an interview with ''IndiaGlitz'', producer [[S. Thanu]] revealed that Rajinikanth had personally asked him to produce the Ranjith-directed film. The producer's commercially successful ''[[Bairavi]]'' (1978) was Rajinikanth's first lead role film and the two had not collaborated since.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz 1\">{{cite web|title=Rajini asked me to produce his next : Kalaipuli S Thanu Interview|language=Tamil|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajini-asked-me-to-produce-his-next--kalaipuli-s-thanu-interview-hindi-videos-60094.html|format=video|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> It was speculated that Rajinikanth's role would be based on a real-life mob boss from [[Chennai]].<ref name=\"Business Standard 1\">{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's next film loosely based on real-life don|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/rajinikanth-s-next-film-loosely-based-on-real-life-don-115081501802_1.html|accessdate=22 August 2015|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|work=[[Business Standard]]|date=15 August 2015}}</ref> [[Santhosh Narayanan]] was confirmed as the film's music composer, continuing his partnership with Ranjith after the latter's previous two films. Ranjith also retained G. Murali, the cinematographer of ''Madras''.\n\nOn 17 August 2015, Ranjith announced the title of the film to be ''Kabali'' and that Rajinikanth would play the role of Kabaliswaran.<ref name=\"Indiaglitz 2\">{{cite web|title=Here is the confirmation on Rajini-Ranjith film title|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/140042.html|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015|ref= |date=17 August 2015}}</ref> The makers of the film had earlier considered using title ''Kaali'', which was the title of [[Kaali (1980 film)|Rajinikanth's 1980 film]]. As that film did not do well in the Tamil Nadu box office at the time, the makers passed on using it for the new film. Another title, ''Kannabhiran'', was also considered but it was later found that the title's rights were already held by director [[Ameer Sultan]] for a future film.<ref name=\"Indiglitz 3\">{{cite web|title=New title for Rajini-Raniith film?|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/140001.html|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=22 August 2015|ref= |date=17 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nIn the film, [[Rajinikanth]] plays the role of an aged crime boss.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' teaser unveiled, watch the superstar in a new gangster avatar|url=http://www.abplive.in/movies/rajinikanths-kabali-teaser-unveiled-watch-the-superstar-in-a-new-gangster-avatar-333752|publisher=ABP Live|date=2 May 2016}}</ref> According to the Telugu newspaper ''[[Eenadu]]'', Rajinikanth, after being impressed with ''[[Nayakan]]'' (1987), requested its director [[Mani Ratnam]] to write a similar script, but the project never materialised; its similarities with Ranjith's script for ''Kabali'' made him accept to star in the latter film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.eenadu.net/pdf/2016/07/21/20160721a_010135003.jpg |title=\u0c30\u0c1c\u0c3f\u0c28\u0c40 \u0c2e\u0c47\u0c28\u0c3f\u0c2f\u0c3e... \u0c07\u0c02\u0c24\u0c3f\u0c02\u0c24 \u0c15\u0c3e\u0c26\u0c2f\u0c3e! |work=[[Eenadu]] |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016 |trans-title=Rajini's mania... is unrestrained! |language=Telugu |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721071017/http://epaper.eenadu.net/pdf/2016/07/21/20160721a_010135003.jpg |archivedate=21 July 2016 |df= }}</ref> [[Dinesh Ravi]], who played the lead in Ranjith's ''[[Attakathi]]'' (2012), and [[Kalaiyarasan]], who played pivotal roles in both of the director's previous films, were also confirmed to be part of the film. An important role was offered to [[Prakash Raj]] initially,<ref name=\"Timyes of India 1\">{{cite news|last1=Balachandran|first1=Logesh|title=Prakash Raj in Rajinikanth-Ranjith film|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Prakash-Raj-in-Rajinikanth-Ranjith-film/articleshow/47733666.cms|accessdate=22 August 2015|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=20 June 2015}}</ref> but later it was said that the role was declined due to scheduling issues and [[John Vijay]] was cast for the role instead.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mrinalini|first1=Sundar|title=I play an educated conman in Veera Sivaji|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/I-play-an-educated-conman-in-Veera-Sivaji/articleshow/50256074.cms|website=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=31 December 2015|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> It was later confirmed that the role of the lead character's wife would be given to [[Radhika Apte]], who was introduced to Tamil films through ''[[Dhoni (film)|Dhoni]]'' (2012).<ref name=\"Filmibeat 1\">{{cite news|last1=Gopinath|first1=Avinash|title=Dhaniskaa bags a role in Rajinikanth's next|url=http://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/news/2015/confirmed-radhika-apte-is-rajinikanth-s-heroine-in-pa-ranjith-s-project-192040.html|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|publisher=[[Oneindia|Filmibeat]]|date=10 August 2015|accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref> [[Dhansika]] was signed to play a supporting character in the film.<ref name=\"IBN 1\">{{cite news|title=Dhaniskaa bags a role in Rajinikanth's next|url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/dhaniskaa-bags-a-role-in-rajinikanths-next-film-1035018.html|accessdate=22 August 2015|agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]|publisher=[[CNN-IBN|IBN]]|date=10 August 2015}}</ref> Soundarya Nandakumar, a television actress best known for her participation in [[Star Vijay]]'s ''[[Airtel Super Singer 3]]'', was chosen for a cameo appearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/Film-projectors-New-age-of-film-promotions/2016/07/16/article3529323.ece|title=Film projectors: New age of film promotions|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\nOn 18 August 2015, director Pa Ranjith announced on his [[Twitter]] page that [[principal photography]] would begin the following week,<ref name=\"New India Express 08-18-15\">{{cite news|title=Rajini's Next with Ranjith Titled Kabali!|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Rajinis-Next-with-Ranjith-Titled-Kabali/2015/08/18/article2979353.ece|accessdate=24 August 2015|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=18 August 2015}}</ref> which was confirmed on 22 August when ''Behindwoods'' covered a [[photo shoot]] which took place on 21 August at [[AVM Studios]] in [[Chennai]]. First schedule of the filming started on [[Vinayagar Chaturthi]] on 17 September 2015 at the Russian Centre of Science and Cultural in Chennai.<ref name=\"Behindwoods 09-18-15\">{{cite news|last1=Saravanakumar|title=Superstar Rajni's Kabali first day shooting...|URL=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-news-15/rajinikanth-appears-stylish-in-the-first-look-poster-of-kabali.html|publisher=Behindwoods|date=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Kabali (soundtrack)\n}}\n[[Santhosh Narayanan]] composed the film's soundtrack and background score of the film. This is the first time, he is scoring for a Rajini-starrer film. The soundtrack album features five songs with lyrics written by [[Kabilan (lyricist)|Kabilan]], [[Vivek (lyricist)|Vivek]], Umadevi and [[Arunraja Kamaraj]] and one song was released as a bonus track after the film's release. The audio rights were acquired by [[Think Music India|Think Music]] and the soundtrack album was released on 12 June 2016 in both original Tamil and [[Hindi]] versions, the [[Telugu language|Telugu]] version was released on 26 June 2016, whereas the [[Malay language|Malay]] version consists of two songs was released on 1 July 2016. A bonus track was released on 5 August 2016. The background score was released on 14 August 2016.\n\n== Release ==\n''Kabali'' was released in Tamil worldwide, along with [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] versions in [[Hindi]], [[Telugu language|Telugu]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], and [[Malay language|Malay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-rajinikanth-kabali-records-shattered-332602|title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' has many feats before the release; know all records it shattered|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=3 June 2016}}</ref> The film was scheduled to be released simultaneously in Singapore and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajinikanths-kabali-to-be-released-in-malay/article8631637.ece|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali to be released in Malay|date=22 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Malik Streams Productions and Distribution, a Malaysian media company, will simultaneously release the film in Malay for exclusive screening in Malaysia alongside the original Tamil version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaivision.com/kabali-tamil-movie-dubbed-malay/|title=Kabali Tamil movie to be dubbed in Malay|last=|first=|date=23 May 2016|website=chennaivision|publisher=chennaivision|access-date=2 June 2016}}</ref> The film was also dubbed in Mandarin<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-36852789 |title = Kabali: How Rajinikanth still packs a punch|work = BBC News|date = 23 July 2016|last1 = Tilak|first1 = Sudha G.}}</ref> and Thai, and was released in Hong Kong, China and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/06/01/rajinikanth-kabali_n_10233732.html|title=Rajinikanth's Upcoming 'Kabali' Is The Hottest Indian Film In The Trade Right Now|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"music\">{{cite news|last1=J|first1=Sam Daniel Stalin|title=From Kabali Makers, a Musical Treat For Rajinikanth's Family|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/from-kabali-makers-a-musical-treat-for-rajinikanths-family-1418090|accessdate=17 July 2016|work=[[NDTV]]|date=12 June 2016|location=[[Chennai]]}}</ref>\n''Kabali'' also premiered at the [[Le Grand Rex]] in Paris, France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chennaivision.com/kabali-premiered-paris-le-grand-rex/|title=Kabali to be premiered at Paris' Le Grand Rex|date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/261216/kabali-goes-to-thailand.html |title = Kabali goes to Thailand|date = 25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\n[[File:Kabali Flight.jpg|thumb|An [[Airbus A320]] of [[AirAsia India]] [[Wrap advertising|wrapped]], featuring [[Rajinikanth]]]]\nAfter the airline [[AirAsia India]] became an official partner for ''Kabali'', an [[Airbus A320]] owned by the airline was [[wrap advertising|wrapped]] with the film's title and an image of [[Rajinikanth]] depicted as Kabaleeshwaran.<ref name=\"music\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajinikanth-radhika-apte-kabali-official-airline-partner-air-asia-tamil-news-160712.html|title=IndiaGlitz&nbsp;\u2014 Rajinikanth Radhika Apte Kabali official airline partner Air Asia&nbsp;\u2014 Tamil Movie News|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=10 June 2016}}</ref> It was the first time a passenger jet had been wrapped for advertising an Indian film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/catalyst/for-these-brands-the-sky-is-the-limit/article8880735.ece|title=For these brands, the sky is the limit|date=21 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> The Indian financial company [[Muthoot Pappachan Group|Muthoot FinCorp]] who is also an official partner of the film produced silver coins embossed with the image of actor as cast in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/business/news/Muthoot-Fincorp-to-offer-silver-coins-on-Kabali/2016/07/14/article3529254.ece|title=Muthoot Fincorp to offer silver coins on 'Kabali' |publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/muthoot-pappachan-group-joins-kabali-mania-issues-silver-coins-with-rajinikanth-image/article8849696.ece|title=Muthoot joins Kabali mania; issues silver coins with Rajinikanth image |publisher=|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> Its [[Teaser campaign|teaser trailer]] was released in April 2016 and went viral in Asia and gained 5 million views in less than 24 hours becoming the most viewed teaser in Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiatvnews.com/entertainment/bollywood-rajinikanth-kabali-teaser-video-326886|title=Watch: Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' teaser unveiled; crosses 1.5 million views within one day|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatandhra.com/movies/movie-news/kabali-becomes-highest-viewed-teaser-in-asia-74853.html|title=Kabali Becomes Highest Viewed Teaser In Asia|publisher=|accessdate=18 June 2016|date=28 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Online piracy issue ===\nOn 19 July 2016, three days prior to the film's worldwide release, it was reported that pirated copies of the film were leaked online in [[darknet]].<ref name=\"IBT\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-kabali-full-movie-leaked-online-download-report-687091 | title=Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' full movie leaked online for download: Report | website=International Business Times | date=19 July 2016 | accessdate=19 July 2016 | author=Hooli, Shekhar H}}</ref> ''[[The Indian Express]]'' reported that although the leaked copies were available only in the darknet, lots of fake links were being circulated in the web. The makers of the film had approached [[Madras High Court]] in anticipation of piracy and had requested the authority to ensure that it does not happen.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/kabali-rajinikanth-leaks-online-three-days-before-release-2922918/ | title=Rajinikanth's Kabali leaks online three days before release | newspaper=The Indian Express | date=19 July 2016 | accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> [[Central Board for Film Certification|CBFC]] chief [[Pahlaj Nihalani]] commented on the issue by saying that the leak had nothing to do with his office in Mumbai and reiterated the fact that Kabali, a Tamil film, was certified by [[Central Board of Film Certification|CBFC]]'s Chennai office. He also added that the leak would not have much effect on the film's [[box office]] collection.\n\nTwo days later, on 21 July 2016, a two-minute long sequence of the film was also leaked online, which subsequently went [[viral video|viral]] on instant messaging app, [[WhatsApp]].<ref name=\"FP-WA\">{{cite news | url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-opening-scene-leaked-on-whatsapp-rajinikanth-film-said-to-be-out-on-dark-web-2906084.html | title='Kabali' opening scene leaked on Whatsapp; Rajinikanth film said to be 'out' on dark web | work=Firstpost | date=21 July 2016 | accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> Commenting on the leak, producer Kalaippuli S Thanu said, \"Watching Thalaivar entry on phone or computer won't give you goosebumps. Say thank you to pirates, let's watch it in theaters from Friday\" through his [[Twitter]] account. ''[[The News Minute]]'' reported that the sequence leak, which carried English as well as Arabic subtitles, could have been released from Gulf countries.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intro-scene-kabali-leaked-outrage-online-producer-says-watch-it-theatres-46855 | title=Intro scene of Kabali leaked! Outrage online, producer says watch it in theatres | publisher=[[The News Minute]] | date=21 July 2016 | accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's release, a partial copy which had been filmed with a mobile phone in a cinema was posted to [[Vimeo]], but was subsequently removed from the website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/07/23/record-debuts-for-tamil-superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-as-producer-discusses-piracy-and-a-sequel|title=Record Debuts For Tamil Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' As Producer Discusses Piracy And A Sequel}}</ref>\n\n=== Alternate ending ===\nThe Malaysian version of the film proceeds beyond the fade to black and offers a concrete ending, stating that Kabali surrendered to the police. This alternate ending was created at the behest of [[Film Censorship Board of Malaysia]], which does not allow showcasing of policemen encouraging violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kabali: Rajinikanth fans witnessed an alternate ending in Malaysian cinemas?|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Kabali-Rajinikanth-fans-witnessed-an-alternate-endingin-Malaysian-cinemas/articleshow/53365772.cms|accessdate=26 July 2016|agency=[[Times News Network|TNN]]|newspaper=The Times of India|date=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali to have different ending in Malaysia|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/rajinikanth-kabali-ending-malaysia-2934856/|accessdate=26 July 2016|agency=[[Press Trust of India|PTI]]|newspaper=The Indian Express|date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=LPF confirmed 'Kabali' to have different ending in Malaysia|url=http://www.themalaysiantimes.com.my/lpf-confirmed-kabali-to-have-different-ending-in-malaysia/|accessdate=26 July 2016|publisher=The Malaysian Times|date=24 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n''Kabali'' was a highly anticipated film throughout the country, including cities like  Chennai,Bangalore, Mumbai, and Hyderabad, but the film received mixed reviews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/220716/kabali-movie-review-slow-burner-without-much-respite.html|title=Kabali movie review: Slow-burner without much respite}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/bollywood/220716/kabali-fever-takes-over-chennai-mumbai-and-bengaluru-fans-watch-5am-show.html|title=Deccanchronicle}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-review-rajinikanth-film-garners-mixed-response-telugu-audience-687491|title=ibtimes|date=22 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.sg/kabali-gets-mixed-reviews-will-this-affect-malay-version-rajinikanths-film-2438|title='Kabali' gets mixed reviews; will this have some impact on its Malay version?|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n''IndiaGlitz'' rated the film 3 out of 5 and called it \"A very different Rajinikanth Experience\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kabali-tamil-movie-review-19903.html|title=Kabali review. Kabali Tamil movie review, story, rating&nbsp;\u2014 IndiaGlitz.com|website=IndiaGlitz|access-date=23 July 2016}}</ref> Behindwoods rated the film 2.75 out of 5 and stated that <nowiki>''Rajinikanth in a different dimension,but Kabali might not work for everyone''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/kabali/kabali-review.html|title=Kabali (aka) Kabaali review|website=Behindwoods|access-date=24 July 2016|date=22 July 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Indian Express]]'' rated the movie 3.5 out of 5 and said that,<nowiki>''Rajinikanth's film lacks pace and mass''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/movie-review/kabali-quick-review-rajinikanth-radhika-apte-2928869/|title=Kabali quick review: Rajinikanth's film lacks pace and mass|date=22 July 2016|access-date=24 July 2016}}</ref> ''Filmibeat'' rated the movie 3 out of 5 stars and stated that <nowiki>''You might be disappointed if you go into the cinema hall keeping in mind the recent hype and hoopla around Kabali\". However, this is definitely Rajinikanth's best in the recent times''</nowiki>.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmibeat.com/tamil/reviews/2016/kabali-movie-review-rating-story-rajinikanth-s-show-with-a-difference-234608.html|title='Kabali' Movie Review & Rating: A Decent Drama Sans Superstardom!|date=21 July 2016|access-date=28 July 2016}}</ref>  ''International Business Times'' rated the film 3.5 out of 5, stating \"Rajnikanth shines in politically charged movie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/kabali-review-rajnikanth-shines-politically-charged-movie-1572019|title=Kabali review: Rajnikanth shines in politically charged movie|date=22 July 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> Baradwaj Rangan of ''[[The Hindu]]'' wrote \"Ranjith\u2019s filmmaking is different too, and not in a good way. Kabali does have some of his trademarks...but the life that infused his earlier films is missing.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rangan |first1=Baradwaj |title=Kabali: An unsatisfying clash between the impulses of star and director |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/Kabali-An-unsatisfying-clash-between-the-impulses-of-star-and-director/article14515117.ece |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=The Hindu |date=22 July 2016 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 70% based on 10 reviews, with an average rating of 6.4/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kabali/|title=Kabali (2016)}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=There is insufficient context for readers unfamiliar with Indian castes to understand exactly what the controversy is. Are there laws that are being broken? Specifics are missing.}}\nSome reviewers attacked the movie for portraying Rajinikanth as a dalit leader. The film was targeted for depicting [[Dalit]] caste which the whole team refused to accept.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/kabali-rajinikanth-movie-review-radhika-apte-dalit-script-2928624/|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali: Backroom script of movie has a Dalit subtext|date=22 July 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-director-pa-ranjith-rajinikanth-approved-politics-dialogue-rhetoric-in-film-2920124.html|title=Kabali director Pa Ranjith: 'Rajinikanth approved politics, dialogue, rhetoric in film' \u2013 Firstpost|date=28 July 2016|newspaper=Firstpost|language=en-US|access-date=6 November 2016}}</ref> However, some dalit outfits referred it as a Dalit movie.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thereel.scroll.in/812882/kabali-film-is-a-response-to-the-2012-dharmapuri-caste-riots-says-dalit-scholar-stalin-rajangam|title='Kabali' film is a response to the 2012 Dharmapuri caste riots, says Dalit scholar Stalin Rajangam|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|newspaper=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/In-Kabali-Dalits-see-a-natty-redeemer/articleshow/53347858.cms|title=In Kabali, Dalits see a natty redeemer&nbsp;\u2014 Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Box office ==\n{{cleanup|section|date=November 2016|reason=Section, which should focus on box office performance, i.e. gross figures, mixes in nett figures. This creates a confusing overview of how the film performed compared to other films which only focus on gross receipts. See [[MOS:FILM]].}}\n''Kabali'' had the highest worldwide opening day for a South Indian film, surpassing the record set by ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning]]'' by earning {{INRConvert|875|m}} on the first day.<ref name=\"International Business Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964 |title='Kabali' Box Office collection |work=International Business Times India|date=4 August 2016}}</ref> The film also had the highest 3-day opening weekend for an Indian film surpassing the {{INRConvert|2.06|b}} record set by ''[[Sultan (2016 film)|Sultan]]'' two weeks earlier as it earned {{INRConvert|2.11|b}}.<ref name=\"International Business Times\" />\n\n=== Disputed gross figures ===\nBox office gross values of {{INR}}6\u20136.75 billion were reported in the first 13 days by several organisations including ''Financial Express'' and ''Indian Express'',<ref name=\"Financial Express 650 crore 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/334390/kabali-box-office-collections-at-over-rs-650-cr-rajinikanth-starrer-is-now-no-1-movie-in-india/4/|title=Rajinikanth starrer Kabali box office collections rise to over Rs 650 crore, turns No. 1 movie in India&nbsp;\u2014 The Financial Express|date=1 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Financial Express 650 crore 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/photos/entertainment-gallery/334390/kabali-box-office-collections-at-over-rs-650-cr-rajinikanth-starrer-is-now-no-1-movie-in-india/3/|title=Rajinikanth starrer Kabali box office collections rise to over Rs 650 crore, turns No. 1 movie in India&nbsp;\u2014 The Financial Express|date=1 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref> which were more than double the estimates made by other sources.<ref name=\"IBT 675 questioned\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|title='Kabali' box office collection: Reports of Rajinikanth-starrer raking in Rs. 675 crore in 13 days are fake|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805214307/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|archivedate=5 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' (IBT) and ''[[Firstpost]]'' criticised these estimates as inflated, explaining the discrepancy as due in part to the addition of \"pre-release business\" figures, such as music and satellite rights sales of {{INR}}2 billion,<ref name=\"Firstpost 600 questioned\" /> being factored into the box office sales totals.<ref name=\"IBT 675 questioned\" /> ''Firstpost'' wrote, \"More conservative estimates put Kabali\u2019s collections at around Rs [3 billion] from worldwide ticket sales.\"<ref name=\"Firstpost 600 questioned\">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/rajinikanth-kabali-has-earned-rs-600-crore-at-the-global-box-office-or-has-it-2932578.html|title=Rajinikanth's Kabali has earned Rs 600 crore at the global box office. Or has it? - Firstpost|date=3 August 2016|publisher=|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref>  IBT's analysts in August 2016 estimated the film's worldwide gross total of its first 13 days at around {{INRConvert|3.5|b}}.<ref name=\"IBT 350 crore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964 |title='Kabali' Box Office collection |work=International Business Times India|date=4 August 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805071102/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-rajinikanth-starrer-beats-7-big-records-baahubali-bahubali-688964|archivedate=5 August 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFigures given in December 2016 by ''Financial Express'' indicated an estimated domestic gross of {{INR}}215 crore and an international gross of {{INR}}262 crore, for a worldwide total of {{INR}}477 crore.<ref name=\"IE Dec 2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/entertainment/rajinikanth-birthday-today-as-superstar-rajni-turns-65-wishes-pour-in/471636/|title=Rajinikanth birthday today; As superstar Rajni turns 65, wishes pour&nbsp;in|date=12 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017}}</ref> A figure of USD$77 million given by Rob Cain in May 2017 converted to approximately {{INR}}493\u2013499 crore.<!--Method: {{INRConvert|494|c|year=2016}} NOTE: Since the Cain source doesn't mention a specific INR value, and is presumably using 2017 US dollars to talk about the gross of a 2016 Indian film, we're forced to extrapolate a range of INR values under 500. --><ref name=\"Forbes 77 mil USD\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/05/11/armies-of-ajith-fans-mobilize-to-blast-vivegam-teaser-to-record-views/|title=Armies Of Ajith Fans Mobilize To Blast 'Vivegam' Teaser To Record Views|first=Rob|last=Cain|publisher=|accessdate=13 May 2017|quote=Kabali, which starred blockbuster hero Rajinikanth, went on to gross nearly 5 billion rupees ($77 million) worldwide, making it the 6th highest grossing Indian film in history at the time.}}</ref> According to ''International Business Times'' in October 2017, ''Kabali''{{'}}s final worldwide gross was around {{INRConvert|286|c}}.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Upadhyaya|first1=Prakash|title=Mersal box office collection: A crowning-moment for Vijay as his film joins Rs 200-crore club|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/mersal-12-days-box-office-collection-crowning-vijay-film-joins-rs-200-crore-club-2nd-weekend-747432|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=30 October 2017|language=en}}</ref> According to [[Box Office India]], the film's final worldwide gross was {{INRConvert|305|c}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=2.0: All India - Overseas - Worldwide Update|url=https://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=4486|work=[[Box Office India]]|date=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== India ===\n''Kabali'' had the highest opening day for a South Indian film in terms of gross revenue, grossing {{INRConvert|530|m}} on the first day of its release in India from all the languages and was just behind the 2015 film ''[[Prem Ratan Dhan Payo]]'' for the highest first day gross in India in a single day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2179|title=Top Openings India&nbsp;\u2014 All Films All Languages|website=Box Office India|date=24 July 2016}}</ref> It also became the first Tamil film to gross {{INRConvert|200|m}} in a single day from Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/bollywood/kabali-box-office-collections-superstar-rajinikanth-2910850.html|title=Kabali box office collections: Let's do the math on Rajinikanth-starrer's numbers|work=[[Firstpost]]}}</ref> ''Kabali'' went on to record the top-earning first weekend in India, grossing {{INRConvert|1.2425|b}} in three days from all its versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2186|title=Salman Khan Has Top Three Domestic Weekends&nbsp;\u2014 Kabali 7th&nbsp;\u2014 Box Office India|work=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2185|title=Kabali Breaks Weekend NETT Collection Record Of Sultan&nbsp;\u2014 Box Office India|work=boxofficeindia.com|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> ''International Business Times'' stated on 4 August 2016 that ''Kabali'' grossed {{INRConvert|2.05|b}} domestically in ten days,<ref name=\"ibtimes.co.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-box-office-collection-reports-rajinikanth-starrer-raking-rs-675-crore-13-days-are-fake-688881|title='Kabali' Box Office Collection Reports|work=International Business Times|date=4 August 2016}}</ref> before later stating on 9 August 2016 that it grossed {{INRConvert|1.96|b}} domestically in seventeen days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-17-days-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-film-moving-towards-rs-200-crore-mark-india-689371|title='Kabali' 17 days box office collection: Rajinikanth's film moving towards Rs. 200 crore mark in India|first=Prakash|last=Upadhyaya|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Overseas ===\n''Kabali'' grossed US$15.70 million ({{INR}}105 crore) till its tenth day.<ref name=\"International Business Times\" /> The film had earned US$11.20 million ({{INR}}75.27 crore) in its first four-day weekend overseas,<ref name=\"Kabali Overseas BoxOffice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/kabali-overseas-box-office-collection-rajinikanths-flick-mints-rs-105-crore-690034|title=Kabali Overseas BoxOffice|publisher=ibtimes|date=16 August 2016}}</ref> breaking the record previously held by ''[[Dhoom 3]]'' (US$10.32 million) as the highest-grossing first weekend for an Indian film in overseas markets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/box-office/special-features/id/748|title=Box Office: Overseas collections of Rajinikanth's Kabali|publisher=[[Bollywood Hungama]]|date=23 July 2016}}</ref> According to ''International Business Times'' in May 2017, the film's final overseas gross was US$15.65&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hooli|first=Shekhar|title=Baahubali 2 overseas box office collection: Rajamouli's film beats Chennai Express, Kabali's lifetime record in 1st weekend|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-overseas-box-office-collection-rajamoulis-film-beats-chennai-express-kabalis-725036|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=1 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Kabali (film)}}\n\n== Sequel ==\nShortly after the film's success, in an interview with Don Groves, S. Thanu said that the initial results exceeded his expectations and that the film\u2019s ending sets up a sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dongroves/2016/07/23/record-debuts-for-tamil-superstar-rajinikanths-kabali-as-producer-discusses-piracy-and-a-sequel/|title=Record Debuts For Tamil Superstar Rajinikanth's 'Kabali' As Producer Discusses Piracy And A Sequel|work=Forbes|date=23 July 2016|access-date=31 July 2016}}</ref> On 25 July 2016, he spoke, \"We created an open climax for ''Kabali''. So, director Ranjith and I are interested in a sequel for this gangster flick. However, Rajinikanth will have to give us the nod to carry on. The film\u2019s collections indicate that it is a sensational hit, and has surpassed all records\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/kollywood/250716/i-am-ready-for-kabali-sequel-kalaipuli-s-thanu.html|title= I am ready for Kabali sequel: Kalaipuli S Thanu |work=Deccan Chronicle|date=25 July 2016|access-date=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe song \"Neruppu Da\" inspired a 2017 film of [[Neruppu Da|same name]] starring [[Vikram Prabhu]]. The title was kept as the film portrayed Vikram Prabhu as firefighter and a fan of Rajinikanth.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.catchnews.com/regional-cinema/vikram-prabhu-turns-producer-with-neruppu-da-a-film-titled-after-kabali-s-song-vikram-pabhu-to-play-rajinikanth-fan-in-neruppu-da-song-1467805906.html |title = Why did Vikram Prabhu copy the title of Kabali's song, Nerrupu da for his maiden production?}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|5071886|Kabali}}\n* {{mojo title|kabali}}\n{{Pa. Ranjith}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime action films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Santhosh Narayanan]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian gangster films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime action films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: USD$ \u2192 US$, Appearence \u2192 Appearance, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kabali_(film)"}
{"title_page": "NeXT", "text_new": "{{About|the computer company||Next (disambiguation){{!}}Next}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = NeXT, Inc.\n| logo                = NeXT logo.svg\n| logo_caption        = NeXT's logo, designed by [[Paul Rand]]\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Computer hardware]]\n* [[Software]]\n}}<!-- types of products or services offered -->\n| fate                = Merged into [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n| successor           = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|1985}}\n| founder             = [[Steve Jobs]]\n| defunct             = {{End date|1997|02|07}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people          = {{Plainlist|\n* Steve Jobs ([[chairman]], [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n* [[Ross Perot]] (director)\n* [[John Patrick Crecine]] (director)\n* [[Avie Tevanian]] ([[vice-president]] of engineering)\n}}\n| products            = {{Collapsible list\n|1= [[NeXT Computer]]\n|2= [[NeXTcube]]\n|3= [[NeXTstation]]\n|4= [[NeXTdimension]]\n|5= [[NeXTSTEP]]\n|6= [[NeXTMail]]\n|7= [[NeXT RISC Workstation]]\n|8= [[NeXT Laser Printer]]\n|9= [[NeXT MegaPixel Display]]\n|10= [[NeXT Music Kit]]\n|11= [[NeXTcube Turbo]]\n|12= [[WriteNow|NeXT port]]\n|13= [[OpenStep]]\n|14= [[WebObjects]]\n}}<!-- some of company's notable products -->\n| num_employees       = 540<!-- peak number of employees -->\n| num_employees_year  = 1992\n| website             = [https://web.archive.org/web/19970412194822/http://www.next.com/ next.com] (archived)\n| footnotes           = <ref name=employees>{{Cite news | title=NeXT Inc. to Drop Hardware 300 losing jobs in strategy shift | date=February 9, 1993 | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''NeXT, Inc.''' (later '''NeXT Computer, Inc.''' and '''NeXT Software, Inc.''') was an American [[computer]] and [[software]] company founded in 1985 by [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer]] co-founder [[Steve Jobs]]. Its name was usually pronounced as \"'''Next'''\". Based in [[Redwood City, California]], the company developed and manufactured a series of [[computer workstation]]s intended for the [[higher education]] and business markets. NeXT was founded by Jobs after he was forced out of Apple, along with several co-workers NeXT introduced the first [[NeXT Computer]] in 1988, and the smaller [[NeXTstation]] in 1990. The NeXT computers experienced relatively limited sales, with estimates of about 50,000 units shipped in total. Nevertheless, their innovative [[Object-oriented programming|object-oriented]] [[NeXTSTEP]] [[operating system]] and [[development environment]] ([[Interface Builder]]) were highly influential.  \n\nThe first major outside investment was from [[Ross Perot]], who invested after seeing a segment about NeXT on a 1986 [[PBS]] documentary titled ''Entrepreneurs''.<ref name=\"RP iPhone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90374043/how-ross-perot-helped-bring-us-the-iphone|title=How Ross Perot befriended Steve Jobs and helped bring us the iPhone|last=McCracken|first=Harry|date=2019-07-09|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In 1987, he invested $20 million in exchange for 16 percent of NeXT's stock and subsequently joined the board of directors in 1988.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/134 134]}}</ref>\n\nNeXT later released much of the NeXTSTEP system as a [[Application programming interface|programming environment]] standard called [[OpenStep]]. NeXT withdrew from the hardware business in 1993 to concentrate on marketing [[OpenStep#OPENSTEP for Mach|OPENSTEP for Mach]], its own OpenStep implementation, for several [[original equipment manufacturer]]s (OEMs). NeXT also developed [[WebObjects]], one of the first enterprise [[Web framework|web application frameworks]]. WebObjects never became very popular because of its initial high price of $50,000, but it remains a prominent early example of a [[Web server]] based on [[Dynamic web page|dynamic page generation]] rather than on [[static content]].\n\nApple purchased NeXT in 1997 for $429 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|USD|429|1997}} million in {{Inflation-year|USD}}) and 1.5 million shares of Apple stock. The merger converted Steve Jobs from Chairman and CEO of NeXT to an advisory role at Apple, the company he had co-founded in 1976;<ref name=\"apple-acquisition\"/><ref name=\"Apple Acquires at Cnet\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-acquires-next-jobs/|title=Apple acquires Next, Jobs|last=Kawamoto|first=Dawn|date=|website=CNET|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315025703/https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-acquires-next-jobs/|archive-date=15 Mar 2020|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and it promised to port NeXT's operating system to Macintosh hardware, combine it with the legacy application layer of [[Mac OS]], and yield [[OS X]].{{primary source inline|date=January 2020}}<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Apple Computer, Inc. Finalizes Acquisition of NeXT Software Inc.|url=http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990117075346/http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html|archivedate=January 17, 1999|publisher=Apple Computer|date=February 7, 1997|accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> In following decades, the new operating system was renamed [[macOS]] and was adapted into the embedded multimedia platforms of [[iOS]], [[watchOS]], and [[tvOS]] to serve as the basis of [[iPhone]] and [[iPad]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\nIn 1985, Apple co-founder Steve Jobs led Apple's SuperMicro division, which was responsible for the development of the [[Macintosh]] and [[Apple Lisa|Lisa]] personal computers. The Macintosh had been successful on university campuses partly because of the [[Apple University Consortium]], which allowed students and institutions to buy the computers at a discount.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780689121357|title=Steve Jobs and the NeXT Big Thing|last=Stross|first=Randall|publisher=Athenium|year=1993|isbn=0-689-12135-0}}</ref>{{rp|56,67}} The consortium had earned more than $50 million on computers by February 1984.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Morrison|first=Jas|title=NeXT, Microsoft tackle objects: NT to gain OpenStep port|work=Fortune|date= February 20, 1984}}</ref>\n\nJobs visited university departments and faculty members to sell Macintosh. Jobs met [[Paul Berg]], a Nobel Laureate in chemistry, at a luncheon held in [[Silicon Valley]] to honor [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], then [[President of France]].<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shannon|first=Victoria|title=Apple losing its polish in Franc| work=[[International New York Times|International Herald Tribune]]|page=11|date=May 22, 2006|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/05/21/business/lobbyside.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060602104905/http://iht.com/articles/2006/05/21/business/lobbyside.php|archivedate=June 2, 2006}}</ref> Berg was frustrated by the expense of teaching students about [[recombinant DNA]] from textbooks instead of in [[Wet laboratory|wet laboratories]], used for the testing and analysis of chemicals, drugs, and other materials or biological matter. Wet labs were prohibitively expensive for lower-level courses and were too complex to be simulated on personal computers of the time. Berg suggested to Jobs to use his influence at Apple to create a \"[[3M computer]]\" workstation for higher education, featuring at least one [[megabyte]] of [[random-access memory]] (RAM), a [[Pixel#Megapixel|megapixel]] display and [[FLOPS|megaFLOPs]] performance, hence the name \"3M\".\n\nJobs was intrigued by Berg's concept of a workstation and contemplated starting a higher education computer company in the fall of 1985, amidst increasing turmoil at Apple. Jobs's division did not release upgraded versions of the Macintosh and much of the [[Macintosh Office]] system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Apple's new Mac push; can Apple Computer succeed in wooing big companies with its Macintosh Office?|last=Fuerst|first=Irene|date=1985-03-15|work=Datamation|page=42}}</ref> As a result, sales plummeted,<ref name=\"West of Eden\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/westofedenendofi00rose_0/page/193|title=West of Eden|last=Rose|first=Frank|publisher=Viking|year=1990|isbn=0-670-81278-1}}</ref>{{rp|193}} and Apple was forced to write off millions of dollars in unsold inventory.<ref name=\"West of Eden\"/>{{rp|227}} Apple's [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) [[John Sculley]] ousted Jobs from his day-to-day role at Apple, replacing him with [[Jean-Louis Gass\u00e9e]] in 1985.<ref name=\"West of Eden\"/>{{rp|291}} Later that year, Jobs began a power struggle to regain control of the company. The [[board of directors]] sided with Sculley while Jobs took a business trip to [[Western Europe]] and the [[Soviet Union]] on behalf of Apple.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/118 118]}}</ref>\n\n===Original NeXT team===\nAfter several months of being sidelined, Jobs resigned from Apple on September 13, 1985. He told the board he was leaving to set up a new computer company, and that he would be taking several Apple employees from the SuperMicro division with him. He also told the board that his new company would not compete with Apple and might even consider licensing its designs back to them to market under the Macintosh brand.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Apple's Jobs Starts New Firm, Targets Education Market|last=Spector|first=G|date=1985-09-24|work=[[eWeek|PC Week]]|page=109}}</ref>\n\nJobs named his new company Next, Inc. A number of former Apple employees followed him to Next, including [[Joanna Hoffman]], [[Bud Tribble]], [[George Crow]], [[Rich Page]], [[Susan Barnes (computing)|Susan Barnes]], [[Susan Kare]], and Dan'l Lewin. After consulting with major educational buyers from around the country, including a follow-up meeting with Paul Berg, a tentative specification for the workstation was drawn up. It was designed to be powerful enough to run wet lab simulations and cheap enough for college students to use in their dormitory rooms.<ref name=\"secondcoming\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/secondcomingofst00deut|url-access=registration|title=Second Coming of Steve Jobs|last=Deutschman|first=Alan|publisher=Broadway Books|year=2000|isbn=0-7679-0432-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/secondcomingofst00deut/page/64 64]}}</ref> Before the specifications were finished, however, Apple sued Next for \"nefarious schemes\" to take advantage of the cofounders' [[Insider|insider information]].<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|75}}<ref name=\"secondcoming\"/>{{rp|44}} Jobs remarked, \"It is hard to think that a $2 billion company with 4,300-plus people couldn't compete with six people in blue jeans.\"<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/> The suit was eventually dismissed before trial.\n\nIn 1986, Jobs recruited the famous graphic designer [[Paul Rand]] to create a brand identity costing $100,000.<ref name=\"rand\"/> Jobs recalled, \"I asked him if he would come up with a few options, and he said, 'No, I will solve your problem for you and you will pay me. You don\u2019t have to use the solution. If you want options go talk to other people.'\"<ref name=\"NeXT logo by Paul Rand\">{{Cite web | title=NeXT logo by Paul Rand | date=March 29, 2010 | publisher=Logo Design Love | url=https://www.logodesignlove.com/next-logo-paul-rand | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Rand created a 20-page brochure detailing the brand, including the precise angle used for the logo (28\u00b0) and a new company name spelling, NeXT.<ref name=\"rand\">{{Cite book|title=Paul Rand|last=Heller|first=Steven|last2=Helfand|first2=Jessica|last3=Lois|first3=George|publisher=Phaidon Press|year=2000|isbn=0-7148-3994-9|pages=256}}</ref>\n\n===1987\u201393: NeXT Computer===\n\n====First generation====\n[[File:First Web Server.jpg|thumb|This original NeXT Computer was used by [[Tim Berners-Lee]] at [[CERN]], and became the world's first [[Web server]] and ran the [[WorldWideWeb|world's first Web browser]] in 1990]]\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=I want some kid at Stanford to be able to cure cancer in his dorm room. | author=Steve Jobs, on the purpose of the new NeXT cube<ref name=\"Fearless Genius\">{{Cite book | title=Fearless Genius: The Digital Revolution in Silicon Valley 1985-2000 | isbn=978-1476752693 | first=Doug | last=Menuez | publisher=Atria Books | date=June 3, 2014 | others=[http://fearlessgenius.org Official website] | oclc=852226582 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lat8AQAAQBAJ&pg=PR20&lpg=PR20&dq=cure+cancer | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nNeXT changed its business plan in mid-1986. The company decided to develop both computer hardware and software, instead of just a low-end workstation. A team led by [[Avie Tevanian]], who had joined the company after working as one of the [[Mach (kernel)|Mach kernel]] engineers at [[Carnegie Mellon University]], was to develop the NeXTSTEP operating system. The hardware division, led by [[Rich Page]] \u2014 one of the cofounders who had previously led the [[Apple Lisa]] team \u2014 designed and developed the hardware. NeXT's first factory was completed in [[Fremont, California]] in 1987.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}} It was capable of producing 150,000 machines per year.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}} NeXT's first workstation was officially named the [[NeXT Computer]], although it was widely termed \"the cube\"<ref name=\"byte\"/> because of its distinctive case, a 1 ft magnesium cube, designed by [[Apple IIc]] case designer [[Frog Design Inc.|Frogdesign]] in accordance with an edict from Jobs.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Bonnera\n| first = Paul\n| title = The heart of a new machine (frogdesign for NeXT computer)hi\n| work = PC/Computing Magazine\n| page = 144\n| date = February 1989}}</ref>\n\nThe original design team had anticipated releasing the computer for [[United States dollar|US$]]3,000 in spring of 1987 to be ready for sale by summer of that year.<ref>{{YouTube|title=Steve Jobs building NeXT|id=WHsHKzYOV2E}}</ref> The NeXT Computer received standing ovations when revealed at a lavish, invitation-only gala event, \"[[NeXT Introduction]] \u2014 the Introduction to the NeXT Generation of Computers for Education\" at the [[Louise M. Davies Symphony Hall]], [[San Francisco]], California on Wednesday October 12, 1988. The following day, selected educators and software developers were invited (for $100 registration fee) to attend the first public technical overview of the NeXT computer at an event called \"The NeXT Day\" held at the San Francisco Hilton. This event gave developers interested in developing NeXT software an insight into the software architecture, [[object-oriented programming]] and developing for the NeXT Computer. The luncheon speaker was Steve Jobs.\n\nThe first machines were tested in 1989, after which NeXT started selling limited numbers to universities with a [[Software testing#Beta testing|beta]] version of the NeXTSTEP operating system installed. Initially the NeXT Computer was targeted at U.S. [[higher education]] establishments only, with a base price of $6,500.<ref name=\"byte\">{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Tom|last2=Baran|first2=Nick|date=November 1988|title=The NeXT Computer|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/byte_article.htm|journal=[[Byte (magazine)|Byte]]|volume=13|issue=12|pages=158\u2013175}}</ref> The machine was widely reviewed in magazines, generally concentrating on the hardware. When asked if he was upset that the computer's debut was delayed by several months, Jobs responded, \"Late? This computer is five years ahead of its time!\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Macintosh Switcher's Guide|last=Standefer|first=Robert|publisher=Wordware Publishing|year=2004|isbn=1-55622-045-6|pages=33|chapter=Evolution of Mac OS X}}</ref>\n\nThe NeXT Computer was based on the new 25 MHz [[Motorola 68030]] [[central processing unit]] (CPU). The [[Motorola 88000]] [[Reduced instruction set computing|RISC]] chip was originally considered, but was not available in sufficient quantities.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Takahashi |first = Ken | title = Motorola making chips in Japan | work = Newsbytes | date = August 29, 1989}}</ref> It included between 8 and 64 [[Megabyte|MB]] of [[random-access memory]] (RAM), a 256 MB [[magneto-optical drive|magneto-optical]] (MO) drive, a 40 MB ([[Paging|swap]]-only), 330 MB, or 660 MB [[hard disk drive]], 10BASE2 [[Ethernet]], [[NuBus]] and a 17-inch ''[[NeXT MegaPixel Display|MegaPixel]]'' grayscale display measuring 1120 by 832 [[pixel]]s. In 1989 a typical new PC, [[Macintosh]], or [[Amiga]] computer included a few megabytes of RAM, a 640\u00d7480 16-color or 320x240 4000-color display, a 10 to 20 megabyte hard drive and few [[Computer network|networking]] capabilities.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = White\n| first = David W.\n| title = Dell System 325 (Hardware Review)\n| work = The Local Area Network Magazine\n| page = 132\n| date = December 1989}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Buyer's guide: benchmarks|last=Krasnoff|first=Barbara|date=December 1989|work=Personal Computing|page=170}}</ref> It is the first computer to have shipped with a general-purpose DSP chip (Motorola 56001) on the motherboard. This supports sophisticated music and sound processing, including the [[Music Kit]] software.\n\nThe magneto-optical drive manufactured by [[Canon Inc.]] is the primary [[mass storage]] device. This drive technology was relatively new to the market, and the NeXT is the first computer to have used it.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\">{{Cite news|title=Developers split over optical drive (NeXT Inc's 256Mbyte erasable magneto-optical drive)|last=Rawles|first=Richard|date=September 19, 1989|work=[[MacWEEK]]|url-status=live|page=3.n33}}</ref> MO drives were cheaper but much slower than hard drives; Jobs negotiated Canon's cost of $150 per blank MO disk down to a retail cost of only $50, and they have an average [[Hard disk drive performance characteristics#SEEKTIME|seek time]] of 96 ms. The design makes it impossible to move files between computers without a network, because each NeXT Computer has only one MO drive and the disk can not be removed without shutting down the system.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\" /> Storage options proved challenging for the first NeXT Computers. The drive's limitations of speed and capacity make it insufficient as the primary medium running the NeXTSTEP operating system.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\" />\n\nIn 1989, NeXT struck a deal for former [[Compaq]] reseller Businessland to sell the NeXT Computer in select markets nationwide. Selling through a retailer was a major change from NeXT's original business model of only selling directly to students and educational institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/25/business/company-news-businessland-deal-seen-for-next-inc.html|title=COMPANY NEWS; Businessland Deal Seen for Next Inc.|date=1989-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-20|url-status=live|agency=Reuters|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Businessland founder David Norman predicted that sales of the NeXT Computer would surpass sales of Compaq computers after 12 months.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Shaffer, Richard | title=NeXT means business now. | work=Personal Computing | date=July 1989 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Canon invested US$100 million in NeXT, giving it a 16.67 percent stake,<ref name=\"canon\">{{Cite news | author=McCarthy, Vance | title=Steve Jobs just says no. | work=Fortune | date=July 17, 1993 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref> making NeXT worth almost $600 million. Canon invested in NeXT with the condition that it would be able to use the NeXTSTEP environment with its own workstations, which would mean a greatly expanded market for the software. After NeXT exited the hardware business, Canon produced a line of PCs, called ''object.station'', including models 31, 41, 50, and 52, specifically designed to run NeXTSTEP for Intel.<ref name=\"object\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/ThirdPartyProducts/ThirdPartyHardware/NeXTSTEPonNonNeXTComputers/IntelHardwareForNeXTStep/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41.html|title=Canon object.station 41|last=Ford|first=Kevin|website=The Best of NeXT Computers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114182612/http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/ThirdPartyProducts/ThirdPartyHardware/NeXTSTEPonNonNeXTComputers/IntelHardwareForNeXTStep/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41.html|archive-date=January 14, 2012|access-date=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Canon also served as NeXT's distributor in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news | last =Garfinkel | first =Simon L | title =Open Door Policy | publisher =NeXTWORLD | date = April 1994 | url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/94.4/94.4.Apr.Japan1.html}}</ref>\n\nThe NeXT Computer was first released on the retail market in 1990, for {{US$|9999|1990}}. NeXT's original investor Ross Perot resigned from the board of directors in June 1991 to dedicate more time to [[Perot Systems]], a [[Plano, Texas]]-based systems integrator.<ref>{{Cite news | title = NeXT may expand two-man board | work = PC Week | page = 125 | date = December 9, 1991}}</ref>\n\n====Second generation====\n[[Image:NeXTstation.jpg|thumb|A [[NeXTstation]] with the original keyboard, mouse and the [[NeXT MegaPixel Display|NeXT MegaPixel]] monitor]]\nNeXT released a second generation of workstations in 1990. The new range included a revised NeXT Computer, renamed the [[NeXTcube]], and the [[NeXTstation]], nicknamed \"the slab\" for its form-factor of a low-rise box. Jobs was explicit in ensuring NeXT staff did not use the nickname \"[[Pizza box form factor|pizza box]]\", so that the NeXT machines would not be compared to competing Sun workstations which already had that nickname. The magneto-optical drive was replaced with a 2.88 MB floppy drive but 2.88 MB floppy disks were expensive and the technology did not supplant the 1.44 MB floppy. Realizing this, NeXT utilized the [[CD-ROM]] drive, which eventually became an industry standard for storage. Color graphics were available on the NeXTstation Color and on the [[NeXTdimension]] [[Video card|graphics processor]] hardware for the NeXTcube. The new computers were cheaper and faster than their predecessors, with the new [[Motorola 68040]] processor.\n\nIn 1992, NeXT launched \"Turbo\" variants of the NeXTcube and NeXTstation with a 33 MHz 68040 processor and maximum RAM capacity increased to 128 MB. NeXT sold 20,000 computers in 1992, and NeXT counted upgraded motherboards on back order as system sales. This is a small number compared with competitors, but the company reported sales of $140 million for the year which encouraged Canon to invest a further $30 million to keep the company afloat.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/200 200]}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=In its existence, Next has sold a total of 50,000 copies of Nextstep, says Jobs. It's not much of an installed base, so he predicts the company will ship 50,000 Nextstep packages in 1993. But Next needs to increase its volume three-fold in order to build enough momentum to forestall Microsoft and Taligent in the object-oriented software business. | source=''UnixWorld'', April 1993<ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\"/>}}\nIn total, 50,000 NeXT machines were sold,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2005/12/next-fans-give-up-the-ghost/|title=NeXT Fans Give Up the Ghost|last=Mortensen|first=Pete|date=2005-12-21|work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|access-date=2011-03-03|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629034820/http://www.wired.com/gadgets/mac/commentary/cultofmac/2005/12/69888?currentPage=1|archive-date=2011-06-29|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\">{{Cite journal | magazine=UnixWorld | publisher=McGraw-Hill | date=April 1993 | page=44 | title=Steve's Gone Soft }}</ref> including thousands to the then super secret [[National Reconnaissance Office]] located in Chantilly, Virginia. NeXT's long-term aim was to migrate to the RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computing) architecture, a processor design strategy intended to increase performance. The project was known as the [[NeXT RISC Workstation]] (NRW). Initially the NRW was to be based on the [[Motorola 88000#Implementations|Motorola 88110]] processor, but due to a lack of confidence in Motorola's commitment to the 88000-series architecture, it was later redesigned around dual [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 601|PowerPC 601s]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra21.html|title=Hardware was great while it lasted|last=Garfinkel|first=Simson L.|date=March 1993|website=NeXTWORLD|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra07.html|title=Canon to buy NeXT factory, design center|last=Lavin|first=Dan|date=March 1993|website=NeXTWORLD|url-status=live|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> NeXT produced some motherboards and enclosures, but exited the hardware business before full production.\n\n====Software applications====\nNeXT computers were delivered with [[Mathematica]] pre-installed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mathematica25.com/1987_nextsignson-2/|title=Mathematica \u2014 Celebrating 25 Years of Contributions, Invention, Discovery, and Education:  Nov. 1987: Steve Jobs signs on to bundle Mathematica with every NeXT computer...|work=mathematica25.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125123920/http://mathematica25.com/1987_nextsignson-2/|archivedate=November 25, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Several developers used the NeXT platform to write pioneering programs. [[Tim Berners-Lee]] used a NeXT Computer in 1990 to create the [[WorldWideWeb|first Web browser]] and Web server;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.w3.org/People/Berners-Lee/WorldWideWeb.html|title=The WorldWideWeb browser|last=Berners-Lee|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Berners-Lee|website=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]|url-status=live|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Ben\">[http://www.netvalley.com/cgi-bin/intval/net_history.pl?chapter=4 Roads and Crossroads of Internet History] Chapter 4: Birth of the Web</ref> accordingly, NeXT was instrumental in the development of the World Wide Web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/the-web/20/385 |title=Inventing the Web |publisher=[[Computer History Museum]] |date= |access-date=August 25, 2016 |quote=The expensive but cutting-edge NeXT computer [\u2026] was famous for rapid prototyping features. These let Tim Berners-Lee create the Web in just three months, but restricted the first browser-editor to these rare machines.}}</ref>\n\nNeXT was used by professors for scientific and engineering applications, and for developing finished newspaper layouts using News. [[George Mason University]] in the early 1990s had a set of NeXT workstations for publishing, as well as Silicon Graphics for CAD/GL and Mathematica for astrophysics. The games ''[[Doom (series)|Doom]]'', ''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]'' were [[Development of Doom#Programming|developed]] by [[id Software]] on NeXT machines. Other games based on the [[Doom engine|''Doom'' engine]], such as ''[[Heretic (video game)|Heretic]]'' and ''[[Hexen: Beyond Heretic]]'' by [[Raven Software]], as well as ''[[Strife (1996 video game)|Strife]]'' by [[Rogue Entertainment]], were also developed on NeXT hardware using id's tools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rome.ro/2006/12/apple-next-merger-birthday.html|title=Apple-NeXT Merger Birthday!|last=Romero|first=John|date=December 20, 2006|website=Planet Rome.ro|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305165006/http://rome.ro/2006/12/apple-next-merger-birthday.html|archive-date=March 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther commercial programs were released for NeXT computers, including Altsys Virtuoso, a vector drawing program with page-layout features which was ported to Mac OS and Microsoft Windows as Aldus FreeHand v4, and the [[Lotus Improv]] [[spreadsheet]] program. The systems were bundled with a number of smaller built-in applications, such as the [[Merriam-Webster]] Collegiate Dictionary, [[Oxford University Press|Oxford]] Quotations, the complete works of [[William Shakespeare]], and the Digital Librarian search engine to access them.\n\n===1993\u201396: NeXT Software===\n[[File:NeXTSTEP desktop.png|thumb|[[NeXTSTEP]], the [[operating system]] used by the NeXTcube and NeXTstation]]\nNeXT started [[porting]] the NeXTSTEP operating system to [[IBM PC compatible]] computers using the [[Intel 80486]] processor in late 1991 because of a change in business strategy to withdraw from the hardware business entirely. A demonstration of the port was displayed at the NeXTWorld Expo in January 1992. By mid-1993 the product was complete and version 3.1, also known as NeXTSTEP 486, was released. Prior to this release, [[Chrysler]] planned to buy 3,000 copies in 1992.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Next Computer Close To a Deal With Chrysler | date=September 8, 1992 | work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nNeXTSTEP 3.x was later ported to [[PA-RISC]]<ref name=\"RISC\">{{Cite news | last =Sherman | first =Lee | title =First NeXT RISC Workstation | work =NeXTWORLD | year =2004 | url =http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/94.4/94.4.Apr.PA-RISC1.html | accessdate=April 14, 2008}}</ref> and [[SPARC]]-based platforms, for a total of four versions: NeXTSTEP/NeXT (for NeXT's 68k \"black boxes\"), NeXTSTEP/Intel, NeXTSTEP/PA-RISC, and NeXTSTEP/SPARC. Although these ports were not widely used, NeXTSTEP gained popularity at institutions such as [[Bank One Corporation|First Chicago NBD]], [[Swiss Bank Corporation]], O'Connor and Company, and other organizations owing to its programming model.<ref>{{Cite news|title=NeXTSTEP: NeXT announces new release of NeXTSTEP & NeXTSTEP Developer. (NeXTSTEP 3.2 and NeXTSTEP Developer 3.2)|date=1993-10-25|work=EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report|page=40}}</ref> It was used by many American federal agencies, such as [[United States Naval Research Laboratory]], the [[National Security Agency]], the [[DARPA|Advanced Research Projects Agency]], the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], and the [[National Reconnaissance Office]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = McCarthy\n| first =Shawn P.\n| title = Next's OS finally is maturing. (NextStep Unix operating system)\n| work = Government Computer News\n| page = 46\n| date = March 6, 1995}}</ref> Some IBM PC clone vendors offered somewhat customized hardware solutions that were delivered running NeXTSTEP on Intel, such as the Elonex NextStation<ref name=\"Elonex PCW\">{{Cite news|title=Elonex NextStation|last=Beard|first=Mat|date=June 1994|work=Personal Computer World}}</ref> and the Canon object.station 41.<ref name=\"Canon object.station PCW\">{{Cite news | last=Bidmead | first=Chris | title=NeXT, please | journal=Personal Computer World |date=February 1995 }}</ref>\n\nNeXT withdrew from the [[Orphaned technology|hardware]] business in 1993 and the company was renamed NeXT Software Inc; consequently, 300 of the 540 staff employees were laid off.<ref name=\"employees\"/> NeXT negotiated to sell the hardware business, including the Fremont factory, to Canon<ref name=\"employees\"/> which later pulled out of the deal. Work on the PowerPC machines was stopped, along with all hardware production. CEO of [[Sun Microsystems]] [[Scott McNealy]] announced plans to invest $10 million in 1993 and use NeXT software in future Sun systems.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Sun invests in Next, which will license NextStep OS for Sparc. | work=InfoWorld | date=November 29, 1993 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref> NeXT partnered with Sun to create [[OpenStep]] which is NeXTSTEP's application layer hosted on a third party operating system.\n\nAfter exiting the hardware business, NeXT focused on other operating systems, in effect returning to the original business plan. New products based on OpenStep were released, including OpenStep Enterprise, a version for Microsoft's [[Windows NT]]. The company launched [[WebObjects]], a platform for building large-scale dynamic web applications. Many large businesses including [[Dell]], [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[MCI Inc.|WorldCom]], and the [[BBC]] used WebObjects for a short time.<ref name=\"webobjects\">{{Cite web | date= June 16, 2005 | first=Johnny | last=Evans | title=Apple releases WebObjects as a free application | work=[[MacCentral]] | url=http://www.macworld.co.uk/news/index.cfm?NewsID=11860 | accessdate=April 14, 2008}}</ref> Eventually [[WebObjects]] was used solely to power Apple's [[iTunes Store]] and most of its corporate website,<ref>{{Cite web |date= June 2, 2003 | last=Dalrymple | first=Jim | title=Xserves power iTunes Music Store, 'America 24/7' | url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1024637/xserve.html | work= [[Macworld]] | accessdate=October 18, 2017 }}</ref> until discontinuing it.\n\n===1996\u201397: purchase by Apple===\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=We went for one of our, you know, signature Steve Jobs walks around Palo Alto, and ... we happened to see someone who was in that meeting from the [Apple] management team who said, 'You guys won easily, no problem. You have nothing to worry about.' | source=[[Avie Tevanian]], presenting NeXT versus Be to Apple<ref name=\"Oral History of Avadis Tevanian, part 2\">{{Cite interview | title=Oral History of Avadis Tevanian, part 2 | publisher=Computer History Museum |interviewer=John Markoff |interviewer2=Hansen Hsu |interviewer3=David C. Brock | first=Avie | last=Tevanian | authorlink=Avie Tevanian | date=April 17, 2017 | location=Mountain View, CA | url=https://archive.computerhistory.org/resources/access/text/2017/07/102740143-05-01-acc.pdf | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nApple Computer announced an intention to acquire NeXT on December 20, 1996.<ref name=\"apple-acquisition\">{{Cite press release|title=Apple Computer, Inc. Agrees to Acquire NeXT Software Inc.|url=http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q1/961220.pr.rel.next.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020208190346/http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q1/961220.pr.rel.next.html|archivedate=February 8, 2002|publisher=Apple Computer|date=December 20, 1996|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> Apple paid $429 million in cash, which went to the initial investors and 1.5 million Apple shares, which went to [[Steve Jobs]], who was deliberately not given cash for his part in the deal.<ref name=\"apple-acquisition\" /><ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Apple files with SEC for Jobs to sell 1.5 million shares\n| work = [[The Seattle Times]]\n| date = June 19, 1997}}</ref> The main purpose of the acquisition was to use NeXTSTEP as a foundation to replace the dated [[classic Mac OS]], instead of [[BeOS]] or the in-development [[Copland (operating system)|Copland]].<ref name=\"kernelthread\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kernelthread.com/publications/appleoshistory/6.html|title=Quest for ''the'' Operating System|last=Singh|first=Amit|date=February 2004|publisher=kernelthread.com|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref> The deal was finalized on February 7, 1997,<ref name=\"archive\">{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html |date=* |title=Apple Computer, Inc. Finalizes Acquisition of NeXT Software Inc. }}, ''Apple Inc.'', February 7, 1997. Retrieved June 25, 2006.</ref> bringing Jobs back to Apple as a consultant, who was later appointed as interim CEO.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Apple May Press Jobs To Be Or Not To Be CEO\n| work = Newsbytes\n| date = March 24, 1998}}</ref> In 2000, Jobs took the CEO position as a permanent assignment, holding the position until his resignation on August 24, 2011; Jobs died six weeks later on October 5, 2011 from complications of a relapsed [[pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor]].<ref>{{Cite web | date=January 5, 2000 | title=Jobs takes Apple CEO job full time |website=[[CNET]] | first=Jim | last=Davis |author2=Kanellos, Michael | url=http://www.news.com/Jobs-takes-Apple-CEO-job-full-time/2100-1001_3-235252.html | accessdate=January 4, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Steve Jobs, Apple co-founder, dies at 56\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/oct/06/steve-jobs-apple-cofounder-dies |work=The Guardian |location=UK |title=Steve Jobs, Apple co-founder, dies at 56 |date=October 6, 2011 |first=Dominic |last=Rushe | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130619055912/http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2011/oct/06/steve-jobs-apple-cofounder-dies | archivedate = June 19, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral NeXT executives replaced their Apple counterparts when Steve Jobs restructured the company's board of directors. Over the next five years the NeXTSTEP operating system was ported to the [[PowerPC]] architecture. At the same time, an Intel port and OpenStep Enterprise toolkit for Windows were both produced. The operating system was code named [[Rhapsody (operating system)|Rhapsody]],<ref>{{Cite web | date=August 6, 1997 | title=What's NeXT? | work=MacObserver | first=Arlen | last=Britton | url=http://www.macobserver.com/columns/whatsnext/articles/080697.shtml | accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> while the toolkit for development on all platforms was called \"Yellow Box\". For backwards compatibility Apple added the \"Blue Box\" to Rhapsody, allowing existing Mac applications to be run in a self-contained cooperative multitasking environment.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Thompson\n| first = Tom\n| title = Rhapsody with blue (Apple's next-generation operating system code-named Rhapsody)\n| work = [[Byte (magazine)|Byte]]\n| page = 26\n| date = April 1997}}</ref>\n\nA server version of the new operating system was released as [[Mac OS X Server 1.0]] in 1999, and the first consumer version, [[Mac OS X 10.0]], in 2001. The OpenStep developer toolkit was renamed [[Cocoa (API)|Cocoa]]. Rhapsody's Blue Box was renamed [[Classic Environment]] and changed to run applications full-screen without requiring a separate window. Apple included an updated version of the original Macintosh toolbox, called [[Carbon (API)|Carbon]], that gave existing Mac applications access to the environment without the constraints of Blue Box.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Sellers\n| first = Dennis\n| title = OS X III: finally, a first-class OS\n| work = Computer User\n| page = 66\n| date = November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Mac OS X Takes Macintosh to New Level\n| work = [[eWeek]]\n| date = July 15, 2002}}</ref> Some of NeXTSTEP's interface features were used in Mac OS X, including the [[Taskbar|Dock]], the [[Services menu]], the [[Finder (software)|Finder]]'s \"[[Miller columns|Column]]\" view, and the [[Cocoa text system]].\n\nNeXTSTEP's processor-independent capabilities were retained in Mac OS X, leading to both PowerPC and Intel x86 versions (although only PowerPC versions were publicly available before 2006). Apple moved to Intel processors by August 2006.<ref>{{Cite press release | title=Apple to Use Intel Microprocessors Beginning in 2006 | url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2005/jun/06intel.html | publisher=Apple Computer|date=June 6, 2005 | accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Corporate culture and community==\nJobs created a different corporate culture at NeXT in terms of facilities, salaries, and benefits. Jobs had experimented with some structural changes at Apple but at NeXT he abandoned conventional corporate structures, instead making a \"community\" with \"members\" instead of employees. There were only two different salaries at NeXT until the early 1990s. Team members who joined before 1986 were paid {{US$|75000|1986}} and those who joined afterward were paid {{US$|50000|1986}}. This caused a few awkward situations where managers were paid less than their employees. Employees were given performance reviews and raises every six months because of the spartan salary plans. To foster openness, all employees had full access to the payrolls, although few employees ever took advantage of the privilege. NeXT's [[health insurance]] plan offered benefits to not only married couples but unmarried couples and same-sex couples, although the latter privilege was later withdrawn due to insurance complications.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|80}} The payroll schedule was also very different from other companies in Silicon Valley at the time because instead of being delivered twice a month in arrears at the end of the pay period, it was delivered once a month in advance.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|289}}\n\nJobs found office space in [[Palo Alto, California]] on 3475 Deer Creek Road, occupying a glass and concrete building which featured a staircase designed by architect [[I. M. Pei]]. The first floor used hardwood flooring and large worktables where the workstations would be assembled. To avoid inventory errors, NeXT used the [[Just-in-time manufacturing|just-in-time]] (JIT) inventory strategy. The company contracted out for all major [[wikt:component|components]] such as mainboards and cases and had the finished components shipped to the first floor for assembly. The second floor was the office space with an open floor plan. The only enclosed rooms were Jobs's office and a few conference rooms.<ref name=\"AppleConfidential\">{{Cite book | first=Owen W. | last=Linzmayer | title=Apple Confidential 2.0 | publisher=No Starch Press | year=2004 |isbn=1-59327-010-0}}</ref>{{rp|323}}\n\nAs NeXT expanded, more office space was needed. The company rented an office at 800 and 900 Chesapeake Drive in Redwood City, also designed by Pei. The architectural centerpiece was a \"floating\" staircase with no visible supports. The open floor plan was retained, although furnishings became luxurious, with $5,000 chairs, $10,000 sofas, and [[Ansel Adams]] prints.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|80}}\n\nNeXT's first campus in Palo Alto was subsequently occupied by [[SAP SE|SAP AG]]. Its second campus in Redwood City was occupied by ApniCure and [[OncoMed|OncoMed Pharmaceuticals Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite news | title=The NeXT big thing: OncoMed finds a home | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2007/10/29/focus6.html?page=all | publisher=American City Business Journals|date=October 28, 2007 | accessdate=June 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe first issue of ''NeXTWORLD'' magazine was printed in 1991. It was published in [[San Francisco]] by Integrated Media and edited by Michael Miley and later Dan Ruby. It was the only mainstream periodical to discuss NeXT computers, the operating system, and NeXT software. The publication was discontinued in 1994 after only four volumes.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Serial Archive Listings for NeXTWORLD | website=The Online Books Page | url=http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/serial?id=nextworld| accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> A ''NeXTWORLD Expo'' followed as a developer [[Convention (meeting)|conference]], held in 1991 and 1992 at the San Francisco Civic Center and in 1993 and 1994 at the [[Moscone Center]] in San Francisco, with Steve Jobs as the keynote speaker.<ref>{{Cite news | title=NeXT makes play for corporate market | work=PC Week | author=NextStep users seek safety in big numbers | date=January 27, 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThough not very profitable, the company had a wide-ranging impact on the computer industry. [[Object-oriented programming]] and [[graphical user interface]]s became more common after the 1988 release of the NeXTcube and NeXTSTEP. The technologically successful platform was often held as the trendsetter when other companies started to emulate the success of NeXT's object-oriented system.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Smith, Carrie | title=NeXT means business now. | work=Wall Street & Technology | date=May 1994 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nWidely seen as a response to NeXT, Microsoft announced the [[Cairo (operating system)|Cairo project]] in 1991; the Cairo specification included similar object-oriented user interface features for a coming consumer version of Windows NT. Although Cairo was ultimately abandoned, some elements were integrated into other projects. By 1994, Microsoft and NeXT were collaborating on a Windows NT port of OpenStep which was never released.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Smith, Carrie | title=NeXT, Microsoft tackle objects: NT to gain OpenStep port. | work=PC Week | date=November 7, 1994 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nBy 1993, [[Taligent]] was considered by the press to be a competitor in objects and operating systems even without any product release, with NeXT being a main point of comparison. For the first few years, Taligent's theoretical newness was often compared to NeXT's older but mature and commercially established platform,<ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\"/><ref name=\"NeXTWORLD Feb 1994\">{{Cite interview | magazine=NeXTWORLD | date=February 1994 | page=23-24 | first=Bud | last=Tribble | interviewer=NeXTWORLD | title=Bud Tribble Explains It All | url=https://archive.org/details/nextworld-1994/ | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Semich\n| first =J. William\n| title = Taligent (Apple, IBM and HP's joint object-oriented operating system)\n| work = Datamation\n| page = 34\n| date = March 15, 1994}}</ref><ref name=\"IEEE Software 1995\">{{Cite journal | title=Taligent Readies a New Development Paradigm | journal=IEEE Software | first=Rich | last=Santalesa | date=1995 | url=https://www.computer.org/csdl/mags/so/1995/02/s2103.pdf | accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> but Taligent's debut release in 1995 was called \"too little, too late\" especially compared to NeXT.<ref name=\"Analysts wary\">{{Cite news | newspaper=SF Gate | date=June 6, 1995 | first=Tom | last=Abate | title=Analysts wary of late software by Taligent | url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Analysts-wary-of-late-software-by-Taligent-3144590.php | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[WebObjects]] failed to achieve wide popularity partly because of the initial high price of US$50,000,<ref name=birthdaywo>{{Cite web |work=MacObserver|url=http://www.macobserver.com/article/2006/03/28.14.shtml |title=Happy Birthday: WebObjects at 10 |accessdate=June 13, 2008 |last=Stewart |first=Graham |year=2006}}</ref> but it remains the first and most prominent early example of a web application server that enabled dynamic page generation based on user interactions as opposed to static content. WebObjects is now bundled with [[macOS Server]] and [[Xcode]].<ref name=birthdaywo/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|San Francisco Bay Area|1990s}}\n* [[NeXT character set]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book | first=Michael | last=Malone | title=Infinite Loop | publisher=Currency | year=1999 | isbn=0-385-48684-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/infiniteloophoww00malo }}\n* {{Cite book | first=Jeffrey S. | last=Young | author2=Simon, William L. | title=iCon: Steve Jobs | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=2005 | isbn=0-471-72083-6 | url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|NeXT}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|NeXT.ogg|2011-10-16}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.next.com/ |title=www.next.com (web archive) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412194822/http://www.next.com/ |archivedate=April 12, 1997}}\n* [https://thenextweb.com/shareables/2011/11/20/watch-steve-jobs-brainstorm-with-the-next-team-in-this-fascinating-video/ Watch Steve Jobs brainstorm with the NeXT team in this fascinating video], November 20, 2011\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180924231203/http://pctimeline.info/workstation/ The Chronology of Workstation Computers]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.next.com/Merger/MergerRelease.html |title=Archived announcement of NeXT's acquisition by Apple |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412201122/http://www.next.com/Merger/MergerRelease.html |archivedate=April 12, 1997}}\n* [http://contracts.onecle.com/apple/next.mer.1996.12.20.shtml Full acquisition/merger contract between Apple and NeXT]\n* [http://simson.net/ref/NeXT/ NeXT Computer Historical Site]\n* [http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/ NeXTWORLD Magazine Archives]\n* [http://www.nextcomputers.org/ NeXTcomputers.org - Welcome to the NeXT world!]\n\n{{Steve Jobs}}\n{{NeXT Computer}}\n{{Apple}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Next}}\n[[Category:NeXT| ]]\n[[Category:Defunct computer companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct software companies]]\n[[Category:Steve Jobs]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Computer companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Computer companies disestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1997 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in California]]\n[[Category:1997 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the computer company||Next (disambiguation){{!}}Next}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = NeXT, Inc.\n| logo                = NeXT logo.svg\n| logo_caption        = NeXT's logo, designed by [[Paul Rand]]\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| industry            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Computer hardware]]\n* [[Software]]\n}}<!-- types of products or services offered -->\n| fate                = Merged into [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\n| successor           = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|1985}}\n| founder             = [[Steve Jobs]]\n| defunct             = {{End date|1997|02|07}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Redwood City, California|Redwood City]], [[California]]\n| hq_location_country = U.S.\n| key_people          = {{Plainlist|\n* Steve Jobs ([[chairman]], [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n* [[Ross Perot]] (director)\n* [[John Patrick Crecine]] (director)\n* [[Avie Tevanian]] ([[vice-president]] of engineering)\n}}\n| products            = {{Collapsible list\n|1= [[NeXT Computer]]\n|2= [[NeXTcube]]\n|3= [[NeXTstation]]\n|4= [[NeXTdimension]]\n|5= [[NeXTSTEP]]\n|6= [[NeXTMail]]\n|7= [[NeXT RISC Workstation]]\n|8= [[NeXT Laser Printer]]\n|9= [[NeXT MegaPixel Display]]\n|10= [[NeXT Music Kit]]\n|11= [[NeXTcube Turbo]]\n|12= [[WriteNow|NeXT port]]\n|13= [[OpenStep]]\n|14= [[WebObjects]]\n}}<!-- some of company's notable products -->\n| num_employees       = 540<!-- peak number of employees -->\n| num_employees_year  = 1992\n| website             = [https://web.archive.org/web/19970412194822/http://www.next.com/ next.com] (archived)\n| footnotes           = <ref name=employees>{{Cite news | title=NeXT Inc. to Drop Hardware 300 losing jobs in strategy shift | date=February 9, 1993 | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''NeXT, Inc.''' (later '''NeXT Computer, Inc.''' and '''NeXT Software, Inc.''') was an American [[computer]] and [[software]] company founded in 1985 by [[Apple Inc.|Apple Computer]] co-founder [[Steve Jobs]]. Its name was usually pronounced as \"'''Next'''\". Based in [[Redwood City, California]], the company developed and manufactured a series of [[computer workstation]]s intended for the [[higher education]] and business markets. NeXT was founded by Jobs after he was forced out of Apple, along with several co-workers NeXT introduced the first [[NeXT Computer]] in 1988, and the smaller [[NeXTstation]] in 1990. The NeXT computers experienced relatively limited sales, with estimates of about 50,000 units shipped in total. Nevertheless, their innovative [[Object-oriented programming|object-oriented]] [[NeXTSTEP]] [[operating system]] and [[development environment]] ([[Interface Builder]]) were highly influential.  \n\nThe first major outside investment was from [[Ross Perot]], who invested after seeing a segment about NeXT on a 1986 [[PBS]] documentary titled ''Entrepreneurs''.<ref name=\"RP iPhone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/90374043/how-ross-perot-helped-bring-us-the-iphone|title=How Ross Perot befriended Steve Jobs and helped bring us the iPhone|last=McCracken|first=Harry|date=2019-07-09|website=Fast Company|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> In 1987, he invested $20 million in exchange for 16 percent of NeXT's stock and subsequently joined the board of directors in 1988.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/134 134]}}</ref>\n\nNeXT later released much of the NeXTSTEP system as a [[Application programming interface|programming environment]] standard called [[OpenStep]]. NeXT withdrew from the hardware business in 1993 to concentrate on marketing [[OpenStep#OPENSTEP for Mach|OPENSTEP for Mach]], its own OpenStep implementation, for several [[original equipment manufacturer]]s (OEMs). NeXT also developed [[WebObjects]], one of the first enterprise [[Web framework|web application frameworks]]. WebObjects never became very popular because of its initial high price of $50,000, but it remains a prominent early example of a [[Web server]] based on [[Dynamic web page|dynamic page generation]] rather than on [[static content]].\n\nApple purchased NeXT in 1997 for $400 million and 1.5 million shares of Apple stock. The merger converted Steve Jobs from Chairman and CEO of NeXT to an advisory role at Apple, the company he had co-founded in 1976;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-acquires-next-jobs/|title=Apple acquires Next, Jobs|last=Kawamoto|first=Dawn|date=|website=CNET|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315025703/https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-acquires-next-jobs/|archive-date=15 Mar 2020|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> and it promised to port NeXT's operating system to Macintosh hardware, combine it with the legacy application layer of [[Mac OS]], and yield [[OS X]].{{primary source inline|date=January 2020}}<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Apple Computer, Inc. Finalizes Acquisition of NeXT Software Inc.|url=http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990117075346/http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html|archivedate=January 17, 1999|publisher=Apple Computer|date=February 7, 1997|accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> In following decades, the new operating system was renamed [[macOS]] and was adapted into the embedded multimedia platforms of [[iOS]], [[watchOS]], and [[tvOS]] to serve as the basis of [[iPhone]] and [[iPad]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\nIn 1985, Apple co-founder Steve Jobs led Apple's SuperMicro division, which was responsible for the development of the [[Macintosh]] and [[Apple Lisa|Lisa]] personal computers. The Macintosh had been successful on university campuses partly because of the [[Apple University Consortium]], which allowed students and institutions to buy the computers at a discount.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780689121357|title=Steve Jobs and the NeXT Big Thing|last=Stross|first=Randall|publisher=Athenium|year=1993|isbn=0-689-12135-0}}</ref>{{rp|56,67}} The consortium had earned more than $50 million on computers by February 1984.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Morrison|first=Jas|title=NeXT, Microsoft tackle objects: NT to gain OpenStep port|work=Fortune|date= February 20, 1984}}</ref>\n\nJobs visited university departments and faculty members to sell Macintosh. Jobs met [[Paul Berg]], a Nobel Laureate in chemistry, at a luncheon held in [[Silicon Valley]] to honor [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], then [[President of France]].<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shannon|first=Victoria|title=Apple losing its polish in Franc| work=[[International New York Times|International Herald Tribune]]|page=11|date=May 22, 2006|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/05/21/business/lobbyside.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060602104905/http://iht.com/articles/2006/05/21/business/lobbyside.php|archivedate=June 2, 2006}}</ref> Berg was frustrated by the expense of teaching students about [[recombinant DNA]] from textbooks instead of in [[Wet laboratory|wet laboratories]], used for the testing and analysis of chemicals, drugs, and other materials or biological matter. Wet labs were prohibitively expensive for lower-level courses and were too complex to be simulated on personal computers of the time. Berg suggested to Jobs to use his influence at Apple to create a \"[[3M computer]]\" workstation for higher education, featuring at least one [[megabyte]] of [[random-access memory]] (RAM), a [[Pixel#Megapixel|megapixel]] display and [[FLOPS|megaFLOPs]] performance, hence the name \"3M\".\n\nJobs was intrigued by Berg's concept of a workstation and contemplated starting a higher education computer company in the fall of 1985, amidst increasing turmoil at Apple. Jobs's division did not release upgraded versions of the Macintosh and much of the [[Macintosh Office]] system.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Apple's new Mac push; can Apple Computer succeed in wooing big companies with its Macintosh Office?|last=Fuerst|first=Irene|date=1985-03-15|work=Datamation|page=42}}</ref> As a result, sales plummeted,<ref name=\"West of Eden\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/westofedenendofi00rose_0/page/193|title=West of Eden|last=Rose|first=Frank|publisher=Viking|year=1990|isbn=0-670-81278-1}}</ref>{{rp|193}} and Apple was forced to write off millions of dollars in unsold inventory.<ref name=\"West of Eden\"/>{{rp|227}} Apple's [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) [[John Sculley]] ousted Jobs from his day-to-day role at Apple, replacing him with [[Jean-Louis Gass\u00e9e]] in 1985.<ref name=\"West of Eden\"/>{{rp|291}} Later that year, Jobs began a power struggle to regain control of the company. The [[board of directors]] sided with Sculley while Jobs took a business trip to [[Western Europe]] and the [[Soviet Union]] on behalf of Apple.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/118 118]}}</ref>\n\n===Original NeXT team===\nAfter several months of being sidelined, Jobs resigned from Apple on September 13, 1985. He told the board he was leaving to set up a new computer company, and that he would be taking several Apple employees from the SuperMicro division with him. He also told the board that his new company would not compete with Apple and might even consider licensing its designs back to them to market under the Macintosh brand.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Apple's Jobs Starts New Firm, Targets Education Market|last=Spector|first=G|date=1985-09-24|work=[[eWeek|PC Week]]|page=109}}</ref>\n\nJobs named his new company Next, Inc. A number of former Apple employees followed him to Next, including [[Joanna Hoffman]], [[Bud Tribble]], [[George Crow]], [[Rich Page]], [[Susan Barnes (computing)|Susan Barnes]], [[Susan Kare]], and Dan'l Lewin. After consulting with major educational buyers from around the country, including a follow-up meeting with Paul Berg, a tentative specification for the workstation was drawn up. It was designed to be powerful enough to run wet lab simulations and cheap enough for college students to use in their dormitory rooms.<ref name=\"secondcoming\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/secondcomingofst00deut|url-access=registration|title=Second Coming of Steve Jobs|last=Deutschman|first=Alan|publisher=Broadway Books|year=2000|isbn=0-7679-0432-X|pages=[https://archive.org/details/secondcomingofst00deut/page/64 64]}}</ref> Before the specifications were finished, however, Apple sued Next for \"nefarious schemes\" to take advantage of the cofounders' [[Insider|insider information]].<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|75}}<ref name=\"secondcoming\"/>{{rp|44}} Jobs remarked, \"It is hard to think that a $2 billion company with 4,300-plus people couldn't compete with six people in blue jeans.\"<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/> The suit was eventually dismissed before trial.\n\nIn 1986, Jobs recruited the famous graphic designer [[Paul Rand]] to create a brand identity costing $100,000.<ref name=\"rand\"/> Jobs recalled, \"I asked him if he would come up with a few options, and he said, 'No, I will solve your problem for you and you will pay me. You don\u2019t have to use the solution. If you want options go talk to other people.'\"<ref name=\"NeXT logo by Paul Rand\">{{Cite web | title=NeXT logo by Paul Rand | date=March 29, 2010 | publisher=Logo Design Love | url=https://www.logodesignlove.com/next-logo-paul-rand | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref> Rand created a 20-page brochure detailing the brand, including the precise angle used for the logo (28\u00b0) and a new company name spelling, NeXT.<ref name=\"rand\">{{Cite book|title=Paul Rand|last=Heller|first=Steven|last2=Helfand|first2=Jessica|last3=Lois|first3=George|publisher=Phaidon Press|year=2000|isbn=0-7148-3994-9|pages=256}}</ref>\n\n===1987\u201393: NeXT Computer===\n\n====First generation====\n[[File:First Web Server.jpg|thumb|This original NeXT Computer was used by [[Tim Berners-Lee]] at [[CERN]], and became the world's first [[Web server]] and ran the [[WorldWideWeb|world's first Web browser]] in 1990]]\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=I want some kid at Stanford to be able to cure cancer in his dorm room. | author=Steve Jobs, on the purpose of the new NeXT cube<ref name=\"Fearless Genius\">{{Cite book | title=Fearless Genius: The Digital Revolution in Silicon Valley 1985-2000 | isbn=978-1476752693 | first=Doug | last=Menuez | publisher=Atria Books | date=June 3, 2014 | others=[http://fearlessgenius.org Official website] | oclc=852226582 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lat8AQAAQBAJ&pg=PR20&lpg=PR20&dq=cure+cancer | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nNeXT changed its business plan in mid-1986. The company decided to develop both computer hardware and software, instead of just a low-end workstation. A team led by [[Avie Tevanian]], who had joined the company after working as one of the [[Mach (kernel)|Mach kernel]] engineers at [[Carnegie Mellon University]], was to develop the NeXTSTEP operating system. The hardware division, led by [[Rich Page]] \u2014 one of the cofounders who had previously led the [[Apple Lisa]] team \u2014 designed and developed the hardware. NeXT's first factory was completed in [[Fremont, California]] in 1987.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}} It was capable of producing 150,000 machines per year.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|72}} NeXT's first workstation was officially named the [[NeXT Computer]], although it was widely termed \"the cube\"<ref name=\"byte\"/> because of its distinctive case, a 1 ft magnesium cube, designed by [[Apple IIc]] case designer [[Frog Design Inc.|Frogdesign]] in accordance with an edict from Jobs.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Bonnera\n| first = Paul\n| title = The heart of a new machine (frogdesign for NeXT computer)hi\n| work = PC/Computing Magazine\n| page = 144\n| date = February 1989}}</ref>\n\nThe original design team had anticipated releasing the computer for [[United States dollar|US$]]3,000 in spring of 1987 to be ready for sale by summer of that year.<ref>{{YouTube|title=Steve Jobs building NeXT|id=WHsHKzYOV2E}}</ref> The NeXT Computer received standing ovations when revealed at a lavish, invitation-only gala event, \"[[NeXT Introduction]] \u2014 the Introduction to the NeXT Generation of Computers for Education\" at the [[Louise M. Davies Symphony Hall]], [[San Francisco]], California on Wednesday October 12, 1988. The following day, selected educators and software developers were invited (for $100 registration fee) to attend the first public technical overview of the NeXT computer at an event called \"The NeXT Day\" held at the San Francisco Hilton. This event gave developers interested in developing NeXT software an insight into the software architecture, [[object-oriented programming]] and developing for the NeXT Computer. The luncheon speaker was Steve Jobs.\n\nThe first machines were tested in 1989, after which NeXT started selling limited numbers to universities with a [[Software testing#Beta testing|beta]] version of the NeXTSTEP operating system installed. Initially the NeXT Computer was targeted at U.S. [[higher education]] establishments only, with a base price of $6,500.<ref name=\"byte\">{{Cite journal|last=Thompson|first=Tom|last2=Baran|first2=Nick|date=November 1988|title=The NeXT Computer|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/byte_article.htm|journal=[[Byte (magazine)|Byte]]|volume=13|issue=12|pages=158\u2013175}}</ref> The machine was widely reviewed in magazines, generally concentrating on the hardware. When asked if he was upset that the computer's debut was delayed by several months, Jobs responded, \"Late? This computer is five years ahead of its time!\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Macintosh Switcher's Guide|last=Standefer|first=Robert|publisher=Wordware Publishing|year=2004|isbn=1-55622-045-6|pages=33|chapter=Evolution of Mac OS X}}</ref>\n\nThe NeXT Computer was based on the new 25 MHz [[Motorola 68030]] [[central processing unit]] (CPU). The [[Motorola 88000]] [[Reduced instruction set computing|RISC]] chip was originally considered, but was not available in sufficient quantities.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Takahashi |first = Ken | title = Motorola making chips in Japan | work = Newsbytes | date = August 29, 1989}}</ref> It included between 8 and 64 [[Megabyte|MB]] of [[random-access memory]] (RAM), a 256 MB [[magneto-optical drive|magneto-optical]] (MO) drive, a 40 MB ([[Paging|swap]]-only), 330 MB, or 660 MB [[hard disk drive]], 10BASE2 [[Ethernet]], [[NuBus]] and a 17-inch ''[[NeXT MegaPixel Display|MegaPixel]]'' grayscale display measuring 1120 by 832 [[pixel]]s. In 1989 a typical new PC, [[Macintosh]], or [[Amiga]] computer included a few megabytes of RAM, a 640\u00d7480 16-color or 320x240 4000-color display, a 10 to 20 megabyte hard drive and few [[Computer network|networking]] capabilities.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = White\n| first = David W.\n| title = Dell System 325 (Hardware Review)\n| work = The Local Area Network Magazine\n| page = 132\n| date = December 1989}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Buyer's guide: benchmarks|last=Krasnoff|first=Barbara|date=December 1989|work=Personal Computing|page=170}}</ref> It is the first computer to have shipped with a general-purpose DSP chip (Motorola 56001) on the motherboard. This supports sophisticated music and sound processing, including the [[Music Kit]] software.\n\nThe magneto-optical drive manufactured by [[Canon Inc.]] is the primary [[mass storage]] device. This drive technology was relatively new to the market, and the NeXT is the first computer to have used it.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\">{{Cite news|title=Developers split over optical drive (NeXT Inc's 256Mbyte erasable magneto-optical drive)|last=Rawles|first=Richard|date=September 19, 1989|work=[[MacWEEK]]|url-status=live|page=3.n33}}</ref> MO drives were cheaper but much slower than hard drives; Jobs negotiated Canon's cost of $150 per blank MO disk down to a retail cost of only $50, and they have an average [[Hard disk drive performance characteristics#SEEKTIME|seek time]] of 96 ms. The design makes it impossible to move files between computers without a network, because each NeXT Computer has only one MO drive and the disk can not be removed without shutting down the system.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\" /> Storage options proved challenging for the first NeXT Computers. The drive's limitations of speed and capacity make it insufficient as the primary medium running the NeXTSTEP operating system.<ref name=\"magneto-optical\" />\n\nIn 1989, NeXT struck a deal for former [[Compaq]] reseller Businessland to sell the NeXT Computer in select markets nationwide. Selling through a retailer was a major change from NeXT's original business model of only selling directly to students and educational institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/25/business/company-news-businessland-deal-seen-for-next-inc.html|title=COMPANY NEWS; Businessland Deal Seen for Next Inc.|date=1989-03-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-20|url-status=live|agency=Reuters|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Businessland founder David Norman predicted that sales of the NeXT Computer would surpass sales of Compaq computers after 12 months.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Shaffer, Richard | title=NeXT means business now. | work=Personal Computing | date=July 1989 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Canon invested US$100 million in NeXT, giving it a 16.67 percent stake,<ref name=\"canon\">{{Cite news | author=McCarthy, Vance | title=Steve Jobs just says no. | work=Fortune | date=July 17, 1993 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref> making NeXT worth almost $600 million. Canon invested in NeXT with the condition that it would be able to use the NeXTSTEP environment with its own workstations, which would mean a greatly expanded market for the software. After NeXT exited the hardware business, Canon produced a line of PCs, called ''object.station'', including models 31, 41, 50, and 52, specifically designed to run NeXTSTEP for Intel.<ref name=\"object\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/ThirdPartyProducts/ThirdPartyHardware/NeXTSTEPonNonNeXTComputers/IntelHardwareForNeXTStep/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41.html|title=Canon object.station 41|last=Ford|first=Kevin|website=The Best of NeXT Computers|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114182612/http://www.kevra.org/TheBestOfNext/ThirdPartyProducts/ThirdPartyHardware/NeXTSTEPonNonNeXTComputers/IntelHardwareForNeXTStep/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41/Canon-object-station41.html|archive-date=January 14, 2012|access-date=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Canon also served as NeXT's distributor in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news | last =Garfinkel | first =Simon L | title =Open Door Policy | publisher =NeXTWORLD | date = April 1994 | url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/94.4/94.4.Apr.Japan1.html}}</ref>\n\nThe NeXT Computer was first released on the retail market in 1990, for {{US$|9999|1990}}. NeXT's original investor Ross Perot resigned from the board of directors in June 1991 to dedicate more time to [[Perot Systems]], a [[Plano, Texas]]-based systems integrator.<ref>{{Cite news | title = NeXT may expand two-man board | work = PC Week | page = 125 | date = December 9, 1991}}</ref>\n\n====Second generation====\n[[Image:NeXTstation.jpg|thumb|A [[NeXTstation]] with the original keyboard, mouse and the [[NeXT MegaPixel Display|NeXT MegaPixel]] monitor]]\nNeXT released a second generation of workstations in 1990. The new range included a revised NeXT Computer, renamed the [[NeXTcube]], and the [[NeXTstation]], nicknamed \"the slab\" for its form-factor of a low-rise box. Jobs was explicit in ensuring NeXT staff did not use the nickname \"[[Pizza box form factor|pizza box]]\", so that the NeXT machines would not be compared to competing Sun workstations which already had that nickname. The magneto-optical drive was replaced with a 2.88 MB floppy drive but 2.88 MB floppy disks were expensive and the technology did not supplant the 1.44 MB floppy. Realizing this, NeXT utilized the [[CD-ROM]] drive, which eventually became an industry standard for storage. Color graphics were available on the NeXTstation Color and on the [[NeXTdimension]] [[Video card|graphics processor]] hardware for the NeXTcube. The new computers were cheaper and faster than their predecessors, with the new [[Motorola 68040]] processor.\n\nIn 1992, NeXT launched \"Turbo\" variants of the NeXTcube and NeXTstation with a 33 MHz 68040 processor and maximum RAM capacity increased to 128 MB. NeXT sold 20,000 computers in 1992, and NeXT counted upgraded motherboards on back order as system sales. This is a small number compared with competitors, but the company reported sales of $140 million for the year which encouraged Canon to invest a further $30 million to keep the company afloat.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff|url-access=registration|title=iCon: Steve Jobs|last=Young|first=Jeffrey S.|last2=Simon|first2=William L.|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2005|isbn=0-471-72083-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff/page/200 200]}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=In its existence, Next has sold a total of 50,000 copies of Nextstep, says Jobs. It's not much of an installed base, so he predicts the company will ship 50,000 Nextstep packages in 1993. But Next needs to increase its volume three-fold in order to build enough momentum to forestall Microsoft and Taligent in the object-oriented software business. | source=''UnixWorld'', April 1993<ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\"/>}}\nIn total, 50,000 NeXT machines were sold,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2005/12/next-fans-give-up-the-ghost/|title=NeXT Fans Give Up the Ghost|last=Mortensen|first=Pete|date=2005-12-21|work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|access-date=2011-03-03|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629034820/http://www.wired.com/gadgets/mac/commentary/cultofmac/2005/12/69888?currentPage=1|archive-date=2011-06-29|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\">{{Cite journal | magazine=UnixWorld | publisher=McGraw-Hill | date=April 1993 | page=44 | title=Steve's Gone Soft }}</ref> including thousands to the then super secret [[National Reconnaissance Office]] located in Chantilly, Virginia. NeXT's long-term aim was to migrate to the RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computing) architecture, a processor design strategy intended to increase performance. The project was known as the [[NeXT RISC Workstation]] (NRW). Initially the NRW was to be based on the [[Motorola 88000#Implementations|Motorola 88110]] processor, but due to a lack of confidence in Motorola's commitment to the 88000-series architecture, it was later redesigned around dual [[PowerPC 600#PowerPC 601|PowerPC 601s]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra21.html|title=Hardware was great while it lasted|last=Garfinkel|first=Simson L.|date=March 1993|website=NeXTWORLD|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra07.html|title=Canon to buy NeXT factory, design center|last=Lavin|first=Dan|date=March 1993|website=NeXTWORLD|url-status=live|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> NeXT produced some motherboards and enclosures, but exited the hardware business before full production.\n\n====Software applications====\nNeXT computers were delivered with [[Mathematica]] pre-installed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mathematica25.com/1987_nextsignson-2/|title=Mathematica \u2014 Celebrating 25 Years of Contributions, Invention, Discovery, and Education:  Nov. 1987: Steve Jobs signs on to bundle Mathematica with every NeXT computer...|work=mathematica25.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125123920/http://mathematica25.com/1987_nextsignson-2/|archivedate=November 25, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Several developers used the NeXT platform to write pioneering programs. [[Tim Berners-Lee]] used a NeXT Computer in 1990 to create the [[WorldWideWeb|first Web browser]] and Web server;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.w3.org/People/Berners-Lee/WorldWideWeb.html|title=The WorldWideWeb browser|last=Berners-Lee|first=Tim|authorlink=Tim Berners-Lee|website=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]|url-status=live|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Ben\">[http://www.netvalley.com/cgi-bin/intval/net_history.pl?chapter=4 Roads and Crossroads of Internet History] Chapter 4: Birth of the Web</ref> accordingly, NeXT was instrumental in the development of the World Wide Web.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/revolution/the-web/20/385 |title=Inventing the Web |publisher=[[Computer History Museum]] |date= |access-date=August 25, 2016 |quote=The expensive but cutting-edge NeXT computer [\u2026] was famous for rapid prototyping features. These let Tim Berners-Lee create the Web in just three months, but restricted the first browser-editor to these rare machines.}}</ref>\n\nNeXT was used by professors for scientific and engineering applications, and for developing finished newspaper layouts using News. [[George Mason University]] in the early 1990s had a set of NeXT workstations for publishing, as well as Silicon Graphics for CAD/GL and Mathematica for astrophysics. The games ''[[Doom (series)|Doom]]'', ''[[Doom II: Hell on Earth]]'' and ''[[Quake (video game)|Quake]]'' were [[Development of Doom#Programming|developed]] by [[id Software]] on NeXT machines. Other games based on the [[Doom engine|''Doom'' engine]], such as ''[[Heretic (video game)|Heretic]]'' and ''[[Hexen: Beyond Heretic]]'' by [[Raven Software]], as well as ''[[Strife (1996 video game)|Strife]]'' by [[Rogue Entertainment]], were also developed on NeXT hardware using id's tools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rome.ro/2006/12/apple-next-merger-birthday.html|title=Apple-NeXT Merger Birthday!|last=Romero|first=John|date=December 20, 2006|website=Planet Rome.ro|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305165006/http://rome.ro/2006/12/apple-next-merger-birthday.html|archive-date=March 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOther commercial programs were released for NeXT computers, including Altsys Virtuoso, a vector drawing program with page-layout features which was ported to Mac OS and Microsoft Windows as Aldus FreeHand v4, and the [[Lotus Improv]] [[spreadsheet]] program. The systems were bundled with a number of smaller built-in applications, such as the [[Merriam-Webster]] Collegiate Dictionary, [[Oxford University Press|Oxford]] Quotations, the complete works of [[William Shakespeare]], and the Digital Librarian search engine to access them.\n\n===1993\u201396: NeXT Software===\n[[File:NeXTSTEP desktop.png|thumb|[[NeXTSTEP]], the [[operating system]] used by the NeXTcube and NeXTstation]]\nNeXT started [[porting]] the NeXTSTEP operating system to [[IBM PC compatible]] computers using the [[Intel 80486]] processor in late 1991 because of a change in business strategy to withdraw from the hardware business entirely. A demonstration of the port was displayed at the NeXTWorld Expo in January 1992. By mid-1993 the product was complete and version 3.1, also known as NeXTSTEP 486, was released. Prior to this release, [[Chrysler]] planned to buy 3,000 copies in 1992.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Next Computer Close To a Deal With Chrysler | date=September 8, 1992 | work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nNeXTSTEP 3.x was later ported to [[PA-RISC]]<ref name=\"RISC\">{{Cite news | last =Sherman | first =Lee | title =First NeXT RISC Workstation | work =NeXTWORLD | year =2004 | url =http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/94.4/94.4.Apr.PA-RISC1.html | accessdate=April 14, 2008}}</ref> and [[SPARC]]-based platforms, for a total of four versions: NeXTSTEP/NeXT (for NeXT's 68k \"black boxes\"), NeXTSTEP/Intel, NeXTSTEP/PA-RISC, and NeXTSTEP/SPARC. Although these ports were not widely used, NeXTSTEP gained popularity at institutions such as [[Bank One Corporation|First Chicago NBD]], [[Swiss Bank Corporation]], O'Connor and Company, and other organizations owing to its programming model.<ref>{{Cite news|title=NeXTSTEP: NeXT announces new release of NeXTSTEP & NeXTSTEP Developer. (NeXTSTEP 3.2 and NeXTSTEP Developer 3.2)|date=1993-10-25|work=EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report|page=40}}</ref> It was used by many American federal agencies, such as [[United States Naval Research Laboratory]], the [[National Security Agency]], the [[DARPA|Advanced Research Projects Agency]], the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], and the [[National Reconnaissance Office]].<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = McCarthy\n| first =Shawn P.\n| title = Next's OS finally is maturing. (NextStep Unix operating system)\n| work = Government Computer News\n| page = 46\n| date = March 6, 1995}}</ref> Some IBM PC clone vendors offered somewhat customized hardware solutions that were delivered running NeXTSTEP on Intel, such as the Elonex NextStation<ref name=\"Elonex PCW\">{{Cite news|title=Elonex NextStation|last=Beard|first=Mat|date=June 1994|work=Personal Computer World}}</ref> and the Canon object.station 41.<ref name=\"Canon object.station PCW\">{{Cite news | last=Bidmead | first=Chris | title=NeXT, please | journal=Personal Computer World |date=February 1995 }}</ref>\n\nNeXT withdrew from the [[Orphaned technology|hardware]] business in 1993 and the company was renamed NeXT Software Inc; consequently, 300 of the 540 staff employees were laid off.<ref name=\"employees\"/> NeXT negotiated to sell the hardware business, including the Fremont factory, to Canon<ref name=\"employees\"/> which later pulled out of the deal. Work on the PowerPC machines was stopped, along with all hardware production. CEO of [[Sun Microsystems]] [[Scott McNealy]] announced plans to invest $10 million in 1993 and use NeXT software in future Sun systems.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Sun invests in Next, which will license NextStep OS for Sparc. | work=InfoWorld | date=November 29, 1993 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref> NeXT partnered with Sun to create [[OpenStep]] which is NeXTSTEP's application layer hosted on a third party operating system.\n\nAfter exiting the hardware business, NeXT focused on other operating systems, in effect returning to the original business plan. New products based on OpenStep were released, including OpenStep Enterprise, a version for Microsoft's [[Windows NT]]. The company launched [[WebObjects]], a platform for building large-scale dynamic web applications. Many large businesses including [[Dell]], [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]], [[MCI Inc.|WorldCom]], and the [[BBC]] used WebObjects for a short time.<ref name=\"webobjects\">{{Cite web | date= June 16, 2005 | first=Johnny | last=Evans | title=Apple releases WebObjects as a free application | work=[[MacCentral]] | url=http://www.macworld.co.uk/news/index.cfm?NewsID=11860 | accessdate=April 14, 2008}}</ref> Eventually [[WebObjects]] was used solely to power Apple's [[iTunes Store]] and most of its corporate website,<ref>{{Cite web |date= June 2, 2003 | last=Dalrymple | first=Jim | title=Xserves power iTunes Music Store, 'America 24/7' | url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1024637/xserve.html | work= [[Macworld]] | accessdate=October 18, 2017 }}</ref> until discontinuing it.\n\n===1996\u201397: purchase by Apple===\n{{quote box | width=25% | align=right | text=We went for one of our, you know, signature Steve Jobs walks around Palo Alto, and ... we happened to see someone who was in that meeting from the [Apple] management team who said, 'You guys won easily, no problem. You have nothing to worry about.' | source=[[Avie Tevanian]], presenting NeXT versus Be to Apple<ref name=\"Oral History of Avadis Tevanian, part 2\">{{Cite interview | title=Oral History of Avadis Tevanian, part 2 | publisher=Computer History Museum |interviewer=John Markoff |interviewer2=Hansen Hsu |interviewer3=David C. Brock | first=Avie | last=Tevanian | authorlink=Avie Tevanian | date=April 17, 2017 | location=Mountain View, CA | url=https://archive.computerhistory.org/resources/access/text/2017/07/102740143-05-01-acc.pdf | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nApple Computer announced an intention to acquire NeXT on December 20, 1996.<ref name=\"apple-acquisition\">{{Cite press release|title=Apple Computer, Inc. Agrees to Acquire NeXT Software Inc.|url=http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q1/961220.pr.rel.next.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020208190346/http://product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q1/961220.pr.rel.next.html|archivedate=February 8, 2002|publisher=Apple Computer|date=December 20, 1996|accessdate=June 13, 2008}}</ref> Apple paid $429 million in cash, which went to the initial investors and 1.5 million Apple shares, which went to [[Steve Jobs]], who was deliberately not given cash for his part in the deal.<ref name=\"apple-acquisition\" /><ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Apple files with SEC for Jobs to sell 1.5 million shares\n| work = [[The Seattle Times]]\n| date = June 19, 1997}}</ref> The main purpose of the acquisition was to use NeXTSTEP as a foundation to replace the dated [[classic Mac OS]], instead of [[BeOS]] or the in-development [[Copland (operating system)|Copland]].<ref name=\"kernelthread\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kernelthread.com/publications/appleoshistory/6.html|title=Quest for ''the'' Operating System|last=Singh|first=Amit|date=February 2004|publisher=kernelthread.com|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref> The deal was finalized on February 7, 1997,<ref name=\"archive\">{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/product.info.apple.com/pr/press.releases/1997/q2/970207.pr.rel.next.html |date=* |title=Apple Computer, Inc. Finalizes Acquisition of NeXT Software Inc. }}, ''Apple Inc.'', February 7, 1997. Retrieved June 25, 2006.</ref> bringing Jobs back to Apple as a consultant, who was later appointed as interim CEO.<ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Apple May Press Jobs To Be Or Not To Be CEO\n| work = Newsbytes\n| date = March 24, 1998}}</ref> In 2000, Jobs took the CEO position as a permanent assignment, holding the position until his resignation on August 24, 2011; Jobs died six weeks later on October 5, 2011 from complications of a relapsed [[pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor]].<ref>{{Cite web | date=January 5, 2000 | title=Jobs takes Apple CEO job full time |website=[[CNET]] | first=Jim | last=Davis |author2=Kanellos, Michael | url=http://www.news.com/Jobs-takes-Apple-CEO-job-full-time/2100-1001_3-235252.html | accessdate=January 4, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Steve Jobs, Apple co-founder, dies at 56\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2011/oct/06/steve-jobs-apple-cofounder-dies |work=The Guardian |location=UK |title=Steve Jobs, Apple co-founder, dies at 56 |date=October 6, 2011 |first=Dominic |last=Rushe | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130619055912/http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2011/oct/06/steve-jobs-apple-cofounder-dies | archivedate = June 19, 2013| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral NeXT executives replaced their Apple counterparts when Steve Jobs restructured the company's board of directors. Over the next five years the NeXTSTEP operating system was ported to the [[PowerPC]] architecture. At the same time, an Intel port and OpenStep Enterprise toolkit for Windows were both produced. The operating system was code named [[Rhapsody (operating system)|Rhapsody]],<ref>{{Cite web | date=August 6, 1997 | title=What's NeXT? | work=MacObserver | first=Arlen | last=Britton | url=http://www.macobserver.com/columns/whatsnext/articles/080697.shtml | accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> while the toolkit for development on all platforms was called \"Yellow Box\". For backwards compatibility Apple added the \"Blue Box\" to Rhapsody, allowing existing Mac applications to be run in a self-contained cooperative multitasking environment.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Thompson\n| first = Tom\n| title = Rhapsody with blue (Apple's next-generation operating system code-named Rhapsody)\n| work = [[Byte (magazine)|Byte]]\n| page = 26\n| date = April 1997}}</ref>\n\nA server version of the new operating system was released as [[Mac OS X Server 1.0]] in 1999, and the first consumer version, [[Mac OS X 10.0]], in 2001. The OpenStep developer toolkit was renamed [[Cocoa (API)|Cocoa]]. Rhapsody's Blue Box was renamed [[Classic Environment]] and changed to run applications full-screen without requiring a separate window. Apple included an updated version of the original Macintosh toolbox, called [[Carbon (API)|Carbon]], that gave existing Mac applications access to the environment without the constraints of Blue Box.<ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Sellers\n| first = Dennis\n| title = OS X III: finally, a first-class OS\n| work = Computer User\n| page = 66\n| date = November 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| title = Mac OS X Takes Macintosh to New Level\n| work = [[eWeek]]\n| date = July 15, 2002}}</ref> Some of NeXTSTEP's interface features were used in Mac OS X, including the [[Taskbar|Dock]], the [[Services menu]], the [[Finder (software)|Finder]]'s \"[[Miller columns|Column]]\" view, and the [[Cocoa text system]].\n\nNeXTSTEP's processor-independent capabilities were retained in Mac OS X, leading to both PowerPC and Intel x86 versions (although only PowerPC versions were publicly available before 2006). Apple moved to Intel processors by August 2006.<ref>{{Cite press release | title=Apple to Use Intel Microprocessors Beginning in 2006 | url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2005/jun/06intel.html | publisher=Apple Computer|date=June 6, 2005 | accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Corporate culture and community==\nJobs created a different corporate culture at NeXT in terms of facilities, salaries, and benefits. Jobs had experimented with some structural changes at Apple but at NeXT he abandoned conventional corporate structures, instead making a \"community\" with \"members\" instead of employees. There were only two different salaries at NeXT until the early 1990s. Team members who joined before 1986 were paid {{US$|75000|1986}} and those who joined afterward were paid {{US$|50000|1986}}. This caused a few awkward situations where managers were paid less than their employees. Employees were given performance reviews and raises every six months because of the spartan salary plans. To foster openness, all employees had full access to the payrolls, although few employees ever took advantage of the privilege. NeXT's [[health insurance]] plan offered benefits to not only married couples but unmarried couples and same-sex couples, although the latter privilege was later withdrawn due to insurance complications.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|80}} The payroll schedule was also very different from other companies in Silicon Valley at the time because instead of being delivered twice a month in arrears at the end of the pay period, it was delivered once a month in advance.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|289}}\n\nJobs found office space in [[Palo Alto, California]] on 3475 Deer Creek Road, occupying a glass and concrete building which featured a staircase designed by architect [[I. M. Pei]]. The first floor used hardwood flooring and large worktables where the workstations would be assembled. To avoid inventory errors, NeXT used the [[Just-in-time manufacturing|just-in-time]] (JIT) inventory strategy. The company contracted out for all major [[wikt:component|components]] such as mainboards and cases and had the finished components shipped to the first floor for assembly. The second floor was the office space with an open floor plan. The only enclosed rooms were Jobs's office and a few conference rooms.<ref name=\"AppleConfidential\">{{Cite book | first=Owen W. | last=Linzmayer | title=Apple Confidential 2.0 | publisher=No Starch Press | year=2004 |isbn=1-59327-010-0}}</ref>{{rp|323}}\n\nAs NeXT expanded, more office space was needed. The company rented an office at 800 and 900 Chesapeake Drive in Redwood City, also designed by Pei. The architectural centerpiece was a \"floating\" staircase with no visible supports. The open floor plan was retained, although furnishings became luxurious, with $5,000 chairs, $10,000 sofas, and [[Ansel Adams]] prints.<ref name=\"The NeXT Big Thing\"/>{{rp|80}}\n\nNeXT's first campus in Palo Alto was subsequently occupied by [[SAP SE|SAP AG]]. Its second campus in Redwood City was occupied by ApniCure and [[OncoMed|OncoMed Pharmaceuticals Inc.]]<ref>{{Cite news | title=The NeXT big thing: OncoMed finds a home | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/stories/2007/10/29/focus6.html?page=all | publisher=American City Business Journals|date=October 28, 2007 | accessdate=June 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe first issue of ''NeXTWORLD'' magazine was printed in 1991. It was published in [[San Francisco]] by Integrated Media and edited by Michael Miley and later Dan Ruby. It was the only mainstream periodical to discuss NeXT computers, the operating system, and NeXT software. The publication was discontinued in 1994 after only four volumes.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Serial Archive Listings for NeXTWORLD | website=The Online Books Page | url=http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/serial?id=nextworld| accessdate=June 13, 2008 }}</ref> A ''NeXTWORLD Expo'' followed as a developer [[Convention (meeting)|conference]], held in 1991 and 1992 at the San Francisco Civic Center and in 1993 and 1994 at the [[Moscone Center]] in San Francisco, with Steve Jobs as the keynote speaker.<ref>{{Cite news | title=NeXT makes play for corporate market | work=PC Week | author=NextStep users seek safety in big numbers | date=January 27, 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThough not very profitable, the company had a wide-ranging impact on the computer industry. [[Object-oriented programming]] and [[graphical user interface]]s became more common after the 1988 release of the NeXTcube and NeXTSTEP. The technologically successful platform was often held as the trendsetter when other companies started to emulate the success of NeXT's object-oriented system.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Smith, Carrie | title=NeXT means business now. | work=Wall Street & Technology | date=May 1994 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nWidely seen as a response to NeXT, Microsoft announced the [[Cairo (operating system)|Cairo project]] in 1991; the Cairo specification included similar object-oriented user interface features for a coming consumer version of Windows NT. Although Cairo was ultimately abandoned, some elements were integrated into other projects. By 1994, Microsoft and NeXT were collaborating on a Windows NT port of OpenStep which was never released.<ref>{{Cite news | author=Smith, Carrie | title=NeXT, Microsoft tackle objects: NT to gain OpenStep port. | work=PC Week | date=November 7, 1994 | publisher=[[InfoTrac|General Reference Center Gold]]}}</ref>\n\nBy 1993, [[Taligent]] was considered by the press to be a competitor in objects and operating systems even without any product release, with NeXT being a main point of comparison. For the first few years, Taligent's theoretical newness was often compared to NeXT's older but mature and commercially established platform,<ref name=\"Unixworld April 1993\"/><ref name=\"NeXTWORLD Feb 1994\">{{Cite interview | magazine=NeXTWORLD | date=February 1994 | page=23-24 | first=Bud | last=Tribble | interviewer=NeXTWORLD | title=Bud Tribble Explains It All | url=https://archive.org/details/nextworld-1994/ | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Semich\n| first =J. William\n| title = Taligent (Apple, IBM and HP's joint object-oriented operating system)\n| work = Datamation\n| page = 34\n| date = March 15, 1994}}</ref><ref name=\"IEEE Software 1995\">{{Cite journal | title=Taligent Readies a New Development Paradigm | journal=IEEE Software | first=Rich | last=Santalesa | date=1995 | url=https://www.computer.org/csdl/mags/so/1995/02/s2103.pdf | accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> but Taligent's debut release in 1995 was called \"too little, too late\" especially compared to NeXT.<ref name=\"Analysts wary\">{{Cite news | newspaper=SF Gate | date=June 6, 1995 | first=Tom | last=Abate | title=Analysts wary of late software by Taligent | url=https://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Analysts-wary-of-late-software-by-Taligent-3144590.php | accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[WebObjects]] failed to achieve wide popularity partly because of the initial high price of US$50,000,<ref name=birthdaywo>{{Cite web |work=MacObserver|url=http://www.macobserver.com/article/2006/03/28.14.shtml |title=Happy Birthday: WebObjects at 10 |accessdate=June 13, 2008 |last=Stewart |first=Graham |year=2006}}</ref> but it remains the first and most prominent early example of a web application server that enabled dynamic page generation based on user interactions as opposed to static content. WebObjects is now bundled with [[macOS Server]] and [[Xcode]].<ref name=birthdaywo/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n* [[NeXT character set]]\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book | first=Michael | last=Malone | title=Infinite Loop | publisher=Currency | year=1999 | isbn=0-385-48684-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/infiniteloophoww00malo }}\n* {{Cite book | first=Jeffrey S. | last=Young | author2=Simon, William L. | title=iCon: Steve Jobs | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=2005 | isbn=0-471-72083-6 | url=https://archive.org/details/iconstevejobsgre00jeff }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|NeXT}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|NeXT.ogg|2011-10-16}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.next.com/ |title=www.next.com (web archive) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412194822/http://www.next.com/ |archivedate=April 12, 1997}}\n* [https://thenextweb.com/shareables/2011/11/20/watch-steve-jobs-brainstorm-with-the-next-team-in-this-fascinating-video/ Watch Steve Jobs brainstorm with the NeXT team in this fascinating video], November 20, 2011\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180924231203/http://pctimeline.info/workstation/ The Chronology of Workstation Computers]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.next.com/Merger/MergerRelease.html |title=Archived announcement of NeXT's acquisition by Apple |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970412201122/http://www.next.com/Merger/MergerRelease.html |archivedate=April 12, 1997}}\n* [http://contracts.onecle.com/apple/next.mer.1996.12.20.shtml Full acquisition/merger contract between Apple and NeXT]\n* [http://simson.net/ref/NeXT/ NeXT Computer Historical Site]\n* [http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/ NeXTWORLD Magazine Archives]\n* [http://www.nextcomputers.org/ NeXTcomputers.org - Welcome to the NeXT world!]\n\n{{Steve Jobs}}\n{{NeXT Computer}}\n{{Apple}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Next}}\n[[Category:NeXT| ]]\n[[Category:Defunct computer companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct software companies]]\n[[Category:Steve Jobs]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Computer companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Computer companies disestablished in 1997]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1997 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in California]]\n[[Category:1997 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Smuckola", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore the wrongly deleted remainder of the citation for accuracy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NeXT"}
